<FIRST>r a AM-GreenhouseConference     03-04 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greenhouse Conference,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Urges Battle Against ``Greenhouse'' Effect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every car should yield 42 miles per gallon and
carbon dioxide emissions should be cut 20 percent to fight the
``greenhouse effect'' that may threaten Earth's climate and human
health, a conference recommended Friday.
   Four hundred scientists and public officials from 13 countries
attended the four-day Global Climate Change meeting that focused on
the warming of the atmosphere and damage to Earth's protective ozone
layer.
   ``The activities of 5 billion people on Earth are clearly
producing changes in the world's climate,'' said Mark Harwell,
director of Cornell University's Global Environment Program. ``In
our lifetimes, and certainly in our children's, climate changes and
other environmental impacts will profoundly affect the way humans
live.''
   The participants called for changes in human activities whose
by-products are gases that may be causing a rise in atmospheric
temperatures, resulting in hotter summers, droughts, more violent
storms, rising sea levels and an increase in diseases.
   The participants urged Congress to pass a more stringent version
of the Clean Air Act, and to stop production by the year 2000 of all
chlorofluorocarbons, which cause the ``greenhouse'' effect.
   They also recommended that the fuel economy of all new cars be
increased by 1{ mpg per year to at least 42 mpg by the year 2000.
Other energy sources, including nuclear plants, should be used more
efficiently and with added safety standards, the participants said.
   The conference also urged that land use and building controls be
enacted to provide for nature conservation, coupled with increased
mass transit that would reduce automobile congestion.
   The conference was convened by Gov. Mario Cuomo, Gov. Tom Keane
of New Jersey, Gov. Madeleine Kunin of Vermont, Cornell University
and the National Governors' Association.
   Among those who addressed the meeting were physicist Carl Sagan;
Ted Turner, head of the CNN cable network; Sen. Albert Gore, Jr.,
D-Tenn.; and Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo.
   The 150 scientists attending the meeting included Vassily Sokolov
of the Soviet Union's Institute of U.S.A. and Canada Studies and Ma
Shijun, chairman of China's Commission on the Environment.
   ``We must learn to understand and live rather than fight natural
forces, including those unleashed by our own activities,'' said the
participants in their final recommendation.
</TEXT>
