<FIRST>r a AM-Stripper'sMom 1stLd-Writethru a0705 03-04 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stripper's Mom, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0705,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge: Mother Linked To Daughter's Suicide Can Get Profits From Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead and 2nd graf; SUBS 7th graf, `Lawyers said...',
to DELETE incorrect reference to first use of ``psychological autopsy.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman convicted of instigating her
daughter's suicide by pushing her to work as a nude dancer will be
allowed to profit from her story, a judge has ruled.
   ``I'm very happy,'' Theresa Jackson said Thursday. ``I'm glad to
get it over with.''
   The agreement between the state and Ms. Jackson, approved
Thursday by Broward Circuit Judge Arthur J. Franza, will require her
to share whatever money she might get from her story with the state
and with her 18-year-old son.
   Ms. Jackson's lawyer, Donna Draves, estimated her client could
receive between $50,000 to $200,000 for film and book rights to her
story.
   Ms. Jackson, 42, was convicted in October 1987 of child abuse,
forgery and procuring a sexual performance by a child. She was
sentenced to a year in jail but is free on bail during an appeal.
   Her 17-year-old daughter, Tina Mancini, shot and killed herself
in the family's Coral Springs home in March 1986. During a two-week
trial, state prosecutors claimed Ms. Jackson traumatized her
daughter by encouraging her to work as a nude dancer, even forging
the girl's birth certificate to make it appear she was older.
   Lawyers said the case was the first in the United States in which
a person was charged with mental child abuse in connection with a
suicide.
   Originally, the state had sought to block Ms. Jackson from
getting any money, citing a never-before-used state law barring
felons from profiting from depictions of their crimes.
   Under terms of Thursday's settlement, the state would receive
about $35,000 for trial and jail costs from any earnings Ms. Jackson
receives from her story. Part of the remaining earnings would be
shared by Ms. Jackson's 18-year-old son.
   Ms. Jackson's former attorney, Kenneth Whitman, has his own claim
pending against Ms. Jackson, contending he is owed $150,000 in
attorney's fees from the trial, and he is seeking to overturn the
agreement with the state. A hearing on that claim is scheduled for
next week.
</TEXT>
