<FIRST>r a PM-AmnesiaVictim     03-04 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Amnesia Victim,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesia Victim Tries to Piece Together His Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About the only clue the stocky, balding
middle-aged man has about his past is the name ``Snuffy'' engraved
on the back of his belt.
   He doesn't know who he is, how he got to Gainesville or anything
before Feb. 8, when he awoke in a wooded area near Shands Hospital
with no wallet and no form of identification.
   He is 5-foot-11, weighs 250 pounds and has a tattoo on his arm.
He was wearing blue jeans, boots, flannel shirt and tinted
prescription glasses when found.
   The hospital said brain scans and other evaluations showed no
signs of a blow to the head or any other physical causes for
amnesia, such as epilepsy or alcohol-related brain malfunction.
   Dr. Ross McElroy, a Shands psychiatrist, said the man is
apparently suffering from a psychological form of amnesia, probably
triggered by a great mental shock or stress.
   The man fears family members may be worrying about him somewhere.
   ``It took two or three days to sort of pull myself through the
fog,'' the man said. ``I spend every waking moment trying to figure
out who ... I am.''
   The man, who is fairly articulate, speaks with a Southwestern
accent and likes to read, sat with mental health counselor W.J.
Tootie Richey and posed for pictures Thursday in hopes of a
breakthrough _ someone who remembers what he can't.
   He said the name ``Snuffy'' doesn't ring a bell for him. ``I
didn't like it at first,'' he said, but ``it seems better than John
Doe.''
   Ms. Richey said her client is able to talk and interact with
people well. He has been reading voraciously, especially newspapers.
   The Alachua County sheriff's office has taken the man's
fingerprints and physical description; there are apparently no
warrants for his arrest.
   There is a good chance that his memory will return, either in
bits and pieces or a sudden rush, authorities said. Most similar
amnesia victims regain most or all their memory within a few days or
weeks.
   McElroy said forgetting an entire life is especially rare.
   The chances are ``you're going to find that there's something
that this guy's getting away from,'' McElroy said.
   ``Whatever I'm responsible for, I want to live up to,'' said the
mystery man.
</TEXT>
