<FIRST>r w PM-Tower Bjt   03-04 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Backers Want Him to Testify Before Full Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower's Senate allies, struggling to gain
the offensive in a tense confirmation battle, are suggesting that
the defense secretary-designate come to the Senate floor and respond
``charge by charge'' to the allegations against him.
   ``If we owe Senator Tower anything, we owe him the right to say,
`I've had my day in court,''' Senate GOP Leader Robert Dole said
Friday as Tower's confirmation chances dimmed further with two
additional Democrats joining the opposition.
   Dole stopped short of turning his suggestion into a formal
proposal, and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said
he would be ``happy to consider any request.''
   Mitchell also said he was troubled by the confirmation
proceedings, in which material from a confidential FBI report that
is damaging to Tower has been leaked in the news media but may not
be discussed openly on the Senate floor. He became the second senior
Democrat in as many days to suggest a closed Senate session to
permit a full airing of the allegations contained in the FBI report.
   Tower has been battling questions of his drinking habits, his
behavior toward women and his lucrative work as a defense industry
consultant after serving as a U.S. arms control negotiator. The FBI
report contains numerous allegations, but Republicans say few if any
of them are corroborated, and insist nothing in it disqualifies him
from the Cabinet post.
   The Senate is in recess until Monday, when debate is expected to
resume on the nomination, although Tower and several senators are
certain to keep the controversy alive over the weekend with
appearances scheduled on television interview programs. The
Associated Press vote count shows 47 Democrats and GOP Sen. Larry
Pressler either committed or leaning against the nomination and 40
Republicans committed or leaning in favor, with the rest undecided.
   The Democrats hold a 55-45 majority in the Senate.
   Dole's surprise suggestion _ only six people have ever been
called to the Senate in 200 years to answer charges against them _
came near the end of a day of debate in which two additional
Democrats announced their opposition and a string of Republicans
complained that Tower was being treated unfairly.
   ``We've got to even up the score somehow,'' said the Senate GOP
leader.
   Arguing that limitations on public references to the FBI report
make it impossible ``to get at the truth,'' Dole suggested bringing
Tower to the floor ``to answer his critics face-to-face,
charge-by-charge, rumor-by-rumor and fact-by-fact.''
   Several Republicans defended Tower earlier in a long day of
debate.
   ``The Senate has abandoned fairness and the object of that
abandonment is John Tower,'' said Sen. Malcolm Wallop , R-Wyo.
   Sen. Ted Stevens said the evidence in the FBI report was so
flimsy that no prosecutor would use it for an indictment, and said
of Tower, ``He is my friend. I thought he was your friend and I want
some justice for my friend.''
   Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho. called on a few Democrats to swing
behind the nomination before partisanship overwhelmed the debate
completely, but the only two Democrats to announce _ conservative
Dennis DeConcini of Arizona and liberal Barbara Mikulski of Maryland
_ said they would oppose confirmation.
   DeConcini had been counted by the White House as a potential
convert to Tower's cause, but in a written statement, he noted the
allegations against Tower and said, ``We cannot take a chance.
   An angry Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., called for the release
of the FBI report, noting the Republican charge that the Democrats
have based their opposition on allegations, not facts.
   ``It's our character that's being assassinated here and I'm sick
and tired of it,'' said Hollings.
   Release of the FBI report is a decision that only the White House
can make.
</TEXT>
