<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-04 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merchants and town officials in this
barrier island resort community have hatched an idea they think will
put them in the pink.
   With nary a squawk Thursday, the Santa Rosa Island Authority's
Development and Leasing Committee endorsed a plan to turn Pensacola
Beach's water tower into a 10-story pink flamingo.
   George Garmon, sales manager for Lamar Advertising Co., a
billboard company in nearby Pensacola, pitched the idea, dubbed
``Project Pink,'' to the panel.
   He said the big bird could be to Pensacola what the Eiffel Tower
is to Paris and the Statue of Liberty is to New York. He even
envisioned an entry in the Guinness Book of World Records.
   Several merchants urged approval. Ross Orenstein, general manager
of Sun Ray Cottage, said shops could sell pink flamingo T-shirts,
bars could serve similarly themed drinks and the community could
have a pink flamingo parade.
   Cost of construction the bird could be borne by business
sponsors, the merchants suggested.
   The proposal goes to the authority's full board next week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pigeons ignored plastic owls, traps
and helium balloons; they were unruffled by high-frequency sound
waves. So authorities are now mulling using a sticky paste to
dissuade the birds from roosting at hangers at an airpark.
   Pigeon droppings have destroyed insulation in the new $40 million
hangars at Chennault Airpark and corroded paint on the KC-135 U.S.
Air Force tankers refurbished at the Boeing Corp. plant, officials
say.
   Lake Charles is considered a bird sanctuary, and a city ordinance
forbids hunting, trapping and shooting birds within city limits.
   At a public hearing to address the problem Thursday, Harry Avery
said his company makes an adhesive that's strong enough to alarm the
pigeons _ and make them stay away from places they've encountered it
_ but too weak to make the birds permanent fixtures.
   The repellant, a clear, sticky gel, is guaranteed for two years,
is non-toxic and does not sting, burn or harm birds, said Avery, of
Hot Foot International in Baton Rouge.
</TEXT>
