<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Summary 1stLd-Writethru a0728 03-04 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Summary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0728,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developments in Eastern Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with strike called; no pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Friday after midnight strike
was called by the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers against Eastern Airlines:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BUSH-MEDIATION RECOMMENDATION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush rejected a mediation board recommendation to use
his authority under provisions of the Railway Labor Act and delay
the strike for 60 more days.
   Bush also warned he would not tolerate sympathy strikes
threatened by other unions to support the Machinists.
   Eastern wanted Bush to stay out of the dispute, saying either a
strike, if it involved pilots, or postponement of the strike, would
lead to bankruptcy.
   The AFL-CIO and 33 senators had asked Bush to intervene to
prevent ``a major disruption of interstate commerce.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>STRIKE PREPARATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern said it would slash up to 75 percent of its weekend
flights, including most services from its Atlanta hub and about 60
other cities.
   The airline said earlier that it was prepared to operate during
any strike and had contracted with 1,100 non-union mechanics to
service planes.
   Eastern's pilots rejected an appeal Thursday by airline owner
Frank Lorenzo for them to sign a new contract and cross Machinists
picket lines.
   Flight attendants said they would honor picket lines.
   Airports nationwide strengthened security and other airlines have
reported surges in sales this week.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MACHINISTS SENT HOME</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern obtained a federal court order and sent its machinists
home, saying the action was intended to prevent sabotage.
   Machinists were given a paid holiday and told to return to work
for shifts starting at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday, one minute after the
strike deadline. Eastern said management personnel would handle
ground duties for the rest of the day.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>NEGOTIATIONS END</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern's offer Thursday was rejected Friday by the Machinists
union, and federal officials said they expected a strike at the
midnight deadline as talks continued between the airline and the
union.
   Eastern said the contract offered would reduce mechanics' pay but
still keep their salaries 13 percent higher than employees who took
a 20 percent pay cut when Lorenzo took over in 1986. It said baggage
handlers' cuts would be no greater than those of other employees.
   At 12:01 a.m., the Machinists went on strike.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LABOR SUPPORT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland and other union leaders said they
doubted there would be any settlement because Lorenzo wants to
dismantle Eastern, which they said is worth about $500 million.
   Other unions pledged support in a plan to block work at other
airlines, railways and sea transport companies if a strike is called.
   The Airline Pilots Association announced that in the event of an
Eastern strike, it would instruct its 40,000 members beginning
Tuesday to strictly follow procedures that would cause ``substantial
delays.''
   Kirkland said the AFL's 14 million members should honor the
Eastern pickets wherever they are legally set up.
   A federal court in Minnesota enjoined Northwest Airlines
employees from staging a sympathy strike. Other airlines and the
union won a U.S. District Court order in Washington that banned
picketing of companies other than Eastern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
