<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stacy Keach didn't mind the 125-foot parachute
plunge into downtown's Glitter Gulch, the motorcycle chase across
the desert or squaring off against ex-football terror Lyle Alzado.
   But don't ask him to repeat that 50-yard swim in 50-degree Lake
Mead _ at least not with his shoes on.
   Keach spent the past week in Las Vegas filming a two-hour
television special ``Murder Takes All _ Mike Hammer in Las Vegas.''
The movie has tested the mettle of Keach, who has a penchant for
doing many of his own stunts.
   One scene called for Hammer to jump from a yacht just before it
explodes and swim 50 yards. Keach, 47, did the stunt wearing a
wetsuit under his clothing to help ward off the chill of the
50-degree water.
   In the first take he also wore his shoes, and learned it was a
serious mistake.
   ``I'm telling you, you almost lost me,'' Keach said after
struggling against the weight of the clothes and trying to kick with
his shoes on.
   Subsequent takes of the scene were shot with Keach swimming
shoeless.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Pat Paulsen has accused his
estranged wife of forgery and harassment in response to a
counterclaim she filed in their divorce proceedings last year.
   Linda Chaney Paulsen had accused Paulsen of seeking a divorce to
get control of the profitable Pat Paulsen Enterprises Inc., which
she managed.
   Chaney Paulsen, 35, was not commenting on the case, but her
attorney, Nathan Davidovich, said she is working on a book, ``Being
Married to a Comedian Is No Laughing Matter.''
   Paulsen, 61, lodged the original complaint in Jefferson County
Court in September after filing for divorce in Denver District
Court, just two months after the couple had married.
   His new motion this week asks that the counterclaim be dismissed,
saying it was filed ``solely to harass, cause an unnecessary delay
in these proceedings and needlessly increase the cost of this
litigation.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surviving members of the Allman Brothers Band,
whose bluesy mix of guitars and keyboards helped define what came to
be known as ``Southern rock'' in the 1970s, are talking about a
reunion album and concert.
   Gregg Allman, Dickey Betts, Butch Trucks and Jai Johnny Johanson
_ better known to some as Jaimoe _ met this week at Trucks' Pegasus
Studios in Tallahassee, Fla.
   ``It was the best conversation the four of us have had in 20
years,'' Trucks said. ``Everybody's definitely into doing it before
we get too old to do it.''
   Trucks said the the band's albums from the late 1960s and early
'70s are ``still getting an awful lot of airplay.''
   Some of the band's hits included ``Rambling Man,'' ``Whippin'
Post'' and ``In Memory of Elizabeth Reed.''
   Right now the classic rock radio format is very popular, and for
the Allman Brothers Band to attract radio airplay they need to act
now, he said.
   Many details of the reunion haven't been worked out, Trucks said.
But he added, ``From talking to Dickey, Gregg and Jaimoe,
everybody's excited about it. It should be fun.''
   The band originally consisted of brothers Duane and Gregg Allman,
Jaimoe, Trucks and bassist Berry Oakley.
   Duane Allman died in a motorcycle accident in October 1971, and
Oakley died in a similar wreck a year later. Keyboard player Chuck
Leavell later joined the group as did bassist Lamar Williams.
Williams died of cancer in 1983.
</TEXT>
