<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former major-leaguer Steve Garvey probably
will continue to have a junior high school named after him, despite
recent allegations that he may have sired two illegitimate children.
   Lincoln Junior High in the town of Lindsay was renamed Steve
Garvey Junior High in 1977, with the thinking that the then-Los
Angeles Dodgers first baseman would be a good example for teen-agers
because of his reputation for clean living.
   Last week, however, it was reported that two women have claimed
they were impregnated by Garvey, who has divorced and remarried
since the renaming.
   Garvey, 40, has said if the children are proved to be his, he
will support them.
   Lindsay Unified School District Superintendent Bob Mohr said he's
unfazed.
   ``He's really been a wonderful model for our kids, and I think a
lot of good has come out of this relationship with Steve Garvey for
our young people,'' Mohr said Friday. ``With that in mind, we're not
about to disassociate ourselves from Steve at this time.
   ``We've hung in with Steve, and it's been good for us, up to this
point.''
</TEXT>
