<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     03-04 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Discovery Launch Set For March 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery and its crew of five
astronauts are scheduled to lift off March 11 on the first of seven
shuttle flights set for 1989.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration selected the
date Friday following a two-day review of the mission. Liftoff was
set for 8:10 a.m. EST.
   ``Our launch teams are not working any significant issues which
are expected to impact a launch next week,'' said Adm. Richard
Truly, NASA's associate administrator for space flight, who directed
the review.
   The mission will be the third for the shuttle program since the
explosive loss of Challenger and its seven astronauts more than
three years ago.
   Discovery made the first post-Challenger flight last September
and was followed by an Atlantis flight in December.
   The latest launch originally was scheduled Feb. 18, but technical
problems forced a series of delays.
   Discovery's crew, headed by commander Michael Coats, is to deploy
a large communications satellite and conduct scientific experiments
during five days in orbit.
   Also on board will be astronauts John Blaha, James Bagian, James
Buchli and Bob Springer.
</TEXT>
