<DOCNO> AP890304-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 0259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Rushdie     03-04 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Rushdie,0884</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets in Balancing Act in Rushdie Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's offer to help cool the furor over the
novel ``The Satanic Verses'' seems a careful attempt to balance its
interests in improving relations with Iran, the West and its own
burgeoning Moslem population.
   The Soviets have defended Iran without condoning the campaign to
kill the book's author. As 15 Western nations withdrew their top
diplomats from Tehran to protest Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's death
threat against Salman Rushdie, the Soviet Union edged closer to Iran
while seeking to ease the uproar.
   ``We need calm,'' Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said
Thursday as he greeted his Spanish counterpart. ``The less emotion
the better for all at the present period. We have to extinguish (the
fire) because nobody needs a fire.''
   The Soviets have not revealed how the dispute could be resolved,
but with an increasingly restive Moslem population of 50 million in
Central Asia, they can ill afford a misstep.
   At first, Soviet officials declined comment on the dispute,
although Shevardnadze was then visiting the Middle East, with Iran
on his itinerary.
   Khomeini ordered his followers Feb. 14 to kill Rushdie, a
naturalized British citizen, because of his book. Moslems say the
book is blasphemous and Iranian clergymen have offered a $5.2
million bounty for Rushdie's death.
   After Shevardnadze discussed the dispute with Iranian officials
during a three-day trip to Tehran that ended Monday, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said: ``The government of
Iran is sincere about finding a settlement of the situation that has
emerged, and the Soviet Union could have a positive role to play.''
   In elaborating the Soviet Union's middle-ground position, the
official news agency Tass said Wednesday that Western countries were
justified in their ``indignation'' over Khomeini's threat.
   But, the news agency added: ``Perhaps Imam Khomeini, the supreme
religious authority in Iran, had no choice proceeding from Koran
teachings, other than denouncing a man who has insulted Islam.''
   ``The denunciation was nothing more, by the way, than the
position of a religious leader. The Iranian government has not
condemned Rushdie to death,'' Tass said, even though Iranian
officials have supported the threat.
   The sympathy toward Iran's religious concerns was unusual in
light of the Kremlin's advocacy of atheism, but reflected
sensitivity to its own Moslem population.
   The Soviet Union's Moslem population is growing much more rapidly
than ethnic Russians who hold the reins of political power. Based on
current trends, the Moslem population will rise to 100 million by
the year 2000, meaning one in every three Soviets will be a Moslem.
   Soviet Moslems were unhappy when the Red Army moved into
neighboring Afghanistan in 1979 to fight Moslem rebels. Siding with
the West in the Rushdie dispute would have angered Soviet Moslems
further at a time when they are becoming increasingly vocal.
   On Feb. 3, Moslems massed in the Uzbek capital of Tashkent to
demand the ouster of their religious leader because, they said, he
was not following religious law and was a pawn of the state. He
later resigned and Moslems are to choose a new leader March 14-15.
   In other signs of new sensitivity to Moslems, the government has
promised to open more mosques and expand an Islamic seminary.
   After Shevardnadze's meetings in Tehran, the Kremlin sought to
play down Khomeini's death threat even though the United States had
asked him to ``raise concerns with the Iranians'' and Britain urged
him to press Iran to back off.
   For Moscow, however, further improving relations with Tehran
carried the day. Iran once lumped the Soviet Union and the United
States together as ``The Great Satan.'' In a sign of the changing
times, Shevardnadze became the highest ranking Soviet to visit Iran
since its 1979 Islamic revolution.
   The Soviet Union's relations with Iran have improved markedly
since it began allowing Moslems more religious freedom and
withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan.
   Iran, gratified by the Afghan pullout, signed an agreement in
December to supply the Soviets with natural gas. Trade is growing
between the countries, and the Soviet Union is helping rebuild areas
of Iran devastated in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   Aside from bringing it closer to Iran, the Soviet offer of
mediation in the Rushdie affair serves a wider foreign policy goal.
It is in line with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's ``new political
thinking,'' which seeks to avoid confrontation and stresses
compromise and cooperation.
   The Soviet tabloid Arguments and Facts said Friday the affair
opens a peacemaking opportunity for the Soviet Union. ``In such
cases, more than ever, assistance is needed from a party that can
take a sober view of things, to help both sides get out of the
difficult situation they created,'' the newspaper said.
   Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez, who met
Thursday in Moscow with Shevardnadze, said the Kremlin mediation
effort had not yet begun.
   ``There was no proposal concerning an intermediary role,'' he
said Friday.
   Shevardnadze is slated to discuss the issue next week in Vienna
with British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe and U.S. Secretary
of State James A. Baker III.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
