<FIRST>r a PM-DroughtWarning     03-04 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Warning,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennsylvania Declares Drought Warning In Eastern Counties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state disaster agency has declared a
drought warning for 16 eastern Pennsylvania counties in the Delaware
River basin and asked people to cut water consumption.
   Lt. Gov. Mark Singel, who chairs the state Emergency Management
Agency, said Friday the shortfall in precipitation and seriously low
reservoirs forced the action.
   ``It's good policy ... and prudent water management,'' Singel
said. ``It will go a long way to relieving a situation that may be
critical in July.''
   People in eastern Pennsylvania are urged to cut water consumption
by 10 percent by taking such steps as checking for water leaks in
their homes and curbing the use of washing machines and dishwashers.
   Singel said problems could start as early as next month if
conservation steps are not taken now. The next step would be a
drought emergency with enforced water cutbacks.
   More than 20 million people in Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey
and Delaware depend upon the Delaware River for their water supply,
Singel said, and rainfall in the river's basin during the past six
months has averaged 4 to 6 inches below normal.
</TEXT>
