<FIRST>r a PM-BarricadedNuns Bjt   03-04 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barricaded Nuns, Bjt,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesting Nuns Ordered Out Of Convent Say They Won't Go</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five nuns protesting the
liberalization of their order plan to spend a sixth month barricaded
in their monastery unless they are convinced of the legitimacy of a
Vatican directive to stop.
   The nuns have refused since Oct. 4 to leave the monastery's
infirmary until the Vatican ruled in the dispute. The nuns said they
feared their mother superior would evict them before the Vatican had
a chance to review their case.
   A spokeswoman for the nuns said Friday they didn't believe the
ruling delivered to them by Roman Catholic Bishop Frank Rodimer of
the Paterson, N.J., diocese was legitimate and that they would
continue their protest.
   ``Nothing came here with a Vatican seal on it,'' said Betty
Sutton, the spokeswoman. ``It's the bishop's final trick to get them
out.''
   The Rev. Timothy Dolan, a spokesman for the Vatican Embassy in
Washington, said an appeal to the Vatican's highest court, the
Apostolica Signatura, could take two weeks or more to be decided.
   Two of the women whose temporary five-year vows expired during
the protest were told they must leave the Monastery of the Most
Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel, the Paterson Roman Catholic
Diocese announced.
   Two others were told they should seek residence in a different
convent, and the fifth, a 71-year-old nun who suffers heart
problems, was told she would be allowed to stay at the monastery,
said Tim Manning, a spokesman for Rodimer.
   The five nuns were among 13 cloistered members of the Order of
Discalced Carmelites at the monastery.
   The nuns said they wanted the monastery returned to the
Carmelites' traditionally austere lifestyle. They had objected to
the introduction of such modern elements as television and candy.
   ``Despite the difficult situation created by some of the
religious, the fundamental principles of religious life were firmly
retained with prudence and charity,'' read the ruling from Cardinal
Jerome Hamer, the head of the Vatican Congregation for the
Religious, which oversees religious communities.
   Manning said he did not know if the five nuns would be forcibly
removed if they refused to leave.
   The mother superior, Prioress Mother Theresa Hewitt, called the
standoff a ``scandal'' when the nuns took over the infirmary and
criticized the unruly members of her order for disrupting the
cloistered lifestyle.
   Mother Hewitt and Rodimer have said the controversy centered on
the rebel nuns' inability to follow their mother superior's orders.
   Sister Eliane, a nun who has acted as a spokeswoman for those not
involved in the protest, said she had no immediate comment.
   ``Not now, not yet,'' she said, adding that the others did not
want to comment.
   Mrs. Sutton said all five women still considered themselves nuns
and part of the order and that they planned to stay until they heard
from the Vatican's highest court.
   ``We entered the monastery for a particular lifestyle, and what
these other, liberal nuns, did is change these rules,'' Sister John
of the Cross, one of the barricaded nuns whose temporary vows
expired, said in a telephone interview shortly after the nuns took
over the infirmary. ``We wouldn't be doing this unless we were
desperate.''
</TEXT>
