<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-04 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Reiterates Drug Denials Folllowing Lewis Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry once
again is enying any involvement with drugs during his visits to a
downtown hotel after the man he went to see was arrested on drug
charges.
   The FBI annouced Friday that Charles Lewis, a central figure in a
pair of federal investigations of the mayor, was arrested in the
Virgin Islands for allegedly selling six to seven grams of cocaine
to undercover FBI agents.
   In a statement issued by his office, Barry said he was aware that
Lewis' arrest would ``raise the specter that something illegal
happened'' when Barry visited Lewis at a Ramada Inn on Dec. 22. ``I
want to repeat again that I never saw any drugs or drug
paraphernalia during my visits with Lewis.''
   A federal grand jury is investigating the circumstances
surrounding Barry's visit to the hotel in December, and a second
investigation involving both Lewis and Barry focuses on the city's
joint personnel project with the Virgin Islands.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspaper Merger Could Begin Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit's two daily newspapers are free to
begin a partial merger Monday, but opponents to the business
agreement are continuing efforts to halt the merger following a
refusal by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist to block the action.
   Rehnquist on Friday turned down an emergency request by attorneys
for Public Citizen, a Washington advocacy group founded by Ralph
Nader that had handled the case on behalf of opponents of the
partial merger.
   He had been asked to delay the partial merger of the Detroit Free
Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., and The Detroit News, owned by
Gannett Co. Inc., until the full Supreme Court could consider a
formal challenge.
   Public Cittizen has asked that the matter be referred to Justice
William Brennan and could ask each justice in turn to consider the
matter.
   However, Brennan, who is under no obligation to act before the
merger takes place, could shorten the process by polling the
justices himself.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Witness Says Hijack Defendant Directly Threatened Passengers, Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused in the 1985 hijacking of a
Jordanian airliner has for the first time been portrayed as directly
threatening the passengers and crew with death.
   A steward, Omar Suliman El Ghadi, 32, testified Friday that in
the initial moments of the hijacking Fawaz Younis ran to the front
of the Boeing 727, pounded on the locked cockpit door with his gun
and shouted, ``If you don't open the door, I will explode it.''
   El Ghadi became the fifth witness in the five-day-old trial at
U.S. District Court to identify Younis as the leader of a group. of
five heavily armed men stormed aboard Royal Jordanian Airlines
flight 402 in Beirut on June 11, 1985.
   Younis, 30, who has pleaded innocent to a six-count indictment
stemming from the hijacking, was captured by FBI agents in
international waters in the Mediterranean Sea more than two years
after the hijacking.
   The trial is seen as a test of a 1984 statute in which U.S.
authorities assert ``long-arm'' jurisdiction over the taking of
American hostages abroad.
   The prosecution rested its case late Friday, and U.S. District
Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. denied a defense motion to dismiss the
indictment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Howard University President To Meet With Students on Atwater Appointment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard University President James Cheek is to
meet today with student representatives to discuss their grievances
in connection with the naming of Republican National Chairman Lee
Atwater as a trustee of the university.
   About 2,000 students, protesting Atwater's the selection, took
over an auditorium stage Friday and forced officials to move a
convocation including presentation of an honorary degree to comedian
Bill Cosby.
   The convocation was moved to an art gallery where there was a
brief ceremony to give Cosby an honorary degree before he left the
campus.
   ``The students at Howard University have a tradition of being
activists,'' university spokesman Alan Hermesch said later. ``When
they feel stongly about issues, they demonstrate.''
   The students said their main complaint was the school's decision
last month to name Atwater, whom they identified with controversial
ads, during George Bush's presidential campaign last year, featuring
Willie Horton, a murderer who attacked a Maryland couple while he
was on furlough from a Massachusetts prison.
   The Horton issue contributed ``to the rising anti-black sentiment
of the American people,'' said Michael Lewis, a spokesman for a
group of students who organized the protest.
</TEXT>
