<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 0710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-ReturningVietnamese     03-04 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Returning Vietnamese,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repatriated Vietnamese Told To Behave When They Get Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese refugees who returned to Hanoi have
been put in a transit camp and told to be sure and get along with
fellow villagers when they are allowed to go home, Hong Kong media
says.
   A chartered jet took the 46 men, 19 women and 10 children back
Thursday in the first large repatriation from Hong Kong. They were
among 11,000 Vietnamese who reached the British colony last year
after its decision that those who could not prove they fled
persecution would be regarded as illegal immigrants.
   The repatriation was arranged by Vietnam and the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees after Vietnam promised not to prosecute
the returnees.
   In Bangkok, the commander of marine police acknowledged that
Thailand has been ``redirecting'' Vietnamese boat people away from
its shores for more than a year. Maj. Gen. Theerachai Reancharoen
said a boatload of 32 Vietnamese was escorted south Friday.
   Reports from Hanoi by Hong Kong's two television stations on
Friday showed the returnees housed at a spacious college an hour's
drive from the airport. Government radio said they would go home to
their villages next week.
   Television Broadcast Ltd. showed them having breakfast, and
quoted one as saying the food was better than they received in Hong
Kong. It quoted members of a family as saying they were glad to be
home and would urge friends not to leave Vietnam.
   Officials of the Vietnamese government and the U.N. refugee
agency visited the boat people Friday, the station reported.
   It said Vietnamese officials warned the boat people not to leave
illegally again and those from the United Nations promised to visit
them in their villages.
   Hong Kong radio said Nguyen Can, director of immigration at the
Vietnamese Interior Ministry, told reporters that the people who
returned earlier had caused trouble in villages.
   Asia Television Ltd., the colony's other television station,
reported that Vietnamese officials would give lectures to the
returnees on how to get along with other villagers.
   A Vietnam News Agency report Friday quoted the Foreign Ministry
as saying the repatriation ``shows our goodwill toward the first
countries of settlement which have met with difficulties caused by
illegal Vietnamese immigrants.''
   Gen. Theerachai said the boat Thailand sent away Friday was
escorted south along the coast, a route leading to Malaysia. The
Thai practice of redirecting boats to Malaysia is widely known, but
officials rarely admit it publicly.
   In a telephone interview, Theerachai said the Vietnamese sail
away voluntarily.
   ``We no longer push off boats from our shores,'' he said. ``We
just redirect the passengers to other countries that can help them
go to Australia, New Zealand and America, places where they want to
go.
   ``We provide them protection, refuel their boats, give them food,
water and medicine. That's humanitarian.''
</TEXT>
