<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Schedule     03-04 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Schedule,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Cuts Weekend Sked By 75 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' pledge to help passengers find
other flights was little consolation early today to thousands left
on the ground when a strike forced the airline to cut 75 percent of
its scheduled flights.
   When Harry Shafer's flight was canceled, Eastern agreed to put
him and the other members of his church group up at a hotel.
   ``They (Eastern) had a block of 30 rooms at the Holiday Inn, but
they just kept sending people out there,'' the 41-year-old DuBois,
Pa., man said. ``By the time we got out there there were none left,
people were arguing and carrying on.''
   The 8,500-member Machinist union, joined by pilots and flight
attendants, went on strike at midnight Friday in a 17-month-old wage
dispute.
   Joseph Leonard, executive vice president and chief operating
officer, said Eastern was suspending service to nearly 60 cities
today and Sunday, but added that the company has drafted an
extensive plan to keep its planes in the air throughout the strike.
   Service was to be maintained to nearly 50 cities, including
Eastern's major flights out of Miami and on its Northeast Shuttle
and South American routes, Leonard said.
   At New York's Kennedy International Airport, Alan Rosen, a
businessman from Woodmere, N.Y., arrived on an Eastern flight just
before the strike was announced and said he believed the walkout
means the end of the airline.
   ``I really think so and it's too bad,'' Rosen said after he got
off Flight 194 from West Palm Beach, which landed at 11:50 p.m., 1{
hours late.
   Leonard said most flights will be suspended at Eastern's Atlanta
hub.
   Eastern ticket offices were extending their hours to help rebook
passengers on canceled flights ``to the extent that is humanly
possible,'' Leonard said.
   Eastern's strike plans also included hiring 1,100 experienced
non-union mechanics and technicians to augment management
maintenance workers, Leonard said.
   The 3,500-member pilots union has voted to honor Machinists union
picket lines, but Leonard predicted some union pilots would cross
the picket lines.
   Only Eastern pilots would be used to fly to the planes, he said,
adding that about 200 management pilots were on call.
   The company also has nonunion employees and supervisors to fill
in for flight attendants, whose 5,900-member union said it also
would support the strike.
</TEXT>
