<FIRST>r a PM-BrothelBuyout     03-04 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brothel Buyout,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bordello Shares Selling in Six States, District of Columbia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Wallstreet is cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bid to take the nation's largest and
best-known legal brothel public through a $23.3 million stock
offering has become an international affair, says the head of the
company handling the sale.
   ``When you've got the most unusual offering in the history of
Wall Street, you get calls from all over the world,'' Eric Walloga,
president of the Tampa, Fla.-based American Wallstreet Securities
Inc., said Friday.
   ``Ever since we announced, we have just been swamped with calls
from Paris, Geneva, Hong Kong and Japan,'' he said. ``I had one
broker in Canada who's called in for a very, very large order.''
   Walloga represents Mustang Ranch Inc., an investors' group made
up primarily of Reno businessmen and attorneys who want to raise the
money to buy the brothel 10 miles east of Reno from owners Joe and
Sally Conforte.
   The Confortes would receive $13 million for the brothel and $5
million for promising not to set up a competing bordello, Walloga
said. The remaining $5.3 million would be used for expansion and
working capital. Prostitution is legal in most of Nevada's rural
counties.
   Under Securities and Exchange Commission rules, none of the
principals in the transaction could discuss it, but Conforte has
said earlier he expected to pocket little profit because most of the
money would go directly to the government for back taxes and
interest he owes.
   ``I owe $12 million to $13 million in taxes and the capital gains
are going to be $4 million to $5 million. I'm going to do my bit to
reduce the deficit,'' said Conforte, who spent 18 months in prison
in 1984 and 1985 for failing to pay his taxes.
   Walloga said six states and the District of Columbia had approved
sales of the stock after it was accepted by the SEC.
   States where the shares are being sold are Florida, Georgia,
Illinois, New York, Connecticut and Colorado. It has not been
approved for sale in Nevada.
   The sale, at $20 a share, began two weeks ago.
   ``There's a lot of novelty interest in the stock. We don't know
how serious people are,'' Walloga said.``Of the people who call to
ask about it, about half call back.
   ``Some people think it's a speculative investment and they're
right. The people who should be buying it are the speculators.''
</TEXT>
