<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Scene     03-04 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Scene,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Workers ``Let Off Steam'' With Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midnight struck and Pat McGarry took a swig of beer,
thrust up a sign promising punishment for scab workers, and walked
across the street separating union headquarters from Eastern
Airlines property.
   The third strike against the airline in 31 years had begun.
   ``They wanted it and now they have it,'' said McGarry, 22, an
aircraft mechanic whose father, Russ, is coordinating national
strike activities for the 8,500-member Machinists union.
   The union went on strike at midnight Friday when talks in
Washington collapsed.
   McGarry was one of the first to reach the gates, locked and
topped with barbed wire. Before him stood police in riot gear.
Behind him, more than 2,500 red-shirted Machinists and supporters
quickly filled the narrow entrance way in front of Eastern hangars.
   For nearly 15 minutes, the chain-link fence took the brunt of the
frustration and anger union members say has been building since
Texas Air President Frank Lorenzo acquired the airline three years
ago. The fence bent under the push but did not give. The padlocked
gates rattled and police raised tear gas guns.
   ``We're just letting off steam,'' said Bob Santos, 41, an Eastern
baggage handler of 21 years. ``Hey, we just want to let them know
we're here.''
   A few paper cups were lobbed over the fence. Soon, they were
replaced by rocks and bottles. The crash of a cinder block startled
some officers. The chips were quickly gathered up and hurled toward
several Eastern management workers, who retreated inside.
   ``Get back. Get back across the street,'' cried a union official.
``We want to keep this legal. We're going to set up pickets, but
we're not going to break any laws.''
   A few union members lurched for the fence, but were pulled back
by union leaders.
   Then car horns blared. Workers heading back to union headquarters
blocked traffic for nearly 10 minutes as an effigy of a ``scab
worker'' was torn apart. The legs of the dummy were tossed above the
crowd. The head rested on the hood of a pickup truck.
   ``I hope Frank Lorenzo is watching,'' said Santos. ``The message
is pretty obvious.''
   After the display, police moved in and herded workers back onto
union property. Twenty-five minutes after midnight, the first of the
workers began to leave.
   ``I think we made our point,'' said Ray Fernandez, a 21-year
mechanic suspended without pay for a month following wildcat
walkouts in February. ``It was really just for show.''
   ``It was loud, but pretty peaceful,'' said Miami police
spokeswoman Myriam Royale.
   No arrests were made, no injuries were reported and no damage was
found, she said.
   Two hours into the strike, most of the workers had left the union
headquarters and pickets were under way at Eastern headquarters,
terminals and cargo facilities.
   ``We're going to keep this peaceful,'' said Wally Haber, senior
general chairman of the Machinists' Miami local. ``We just needed to
let off some steam.''
</TEXT>
