<FIRST>r i PM-France-Scandal     03-04 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Scandal,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businessman Linked To Socialists Charged In French Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman linked to the governing Socialists has
been charged with insider trading, making him the sixth person
accused in a scandal that has embarrassed the government, a news
report said.
   Max Theret, a Paris investor who has backed Socialist Party
candidates, was charged Friday by Investigating Magistrate Edith
Boizette with insider trading, the news agency Agence-France Press
said.
   Quoting unidentified legal sources, the agency said Theret is
accused of illegally buying shares of a U.S. company, Triangle
Industries Inc., before the French state-owned aluminum manufacturer
Pichiney SA offered a higher price in a successful takeover. The
Pichiney offer sent the stock's price soaring.
   On Feb. 16, three men also were charged with insider trading:
Paris stockbrokers Pierre-Alain Marsan and Ricardo Zavala; and
Robert Reiplinger, Theret's partner in a Paris investment firm. Also
charged in the scandal that day was Roger-Patrice Pelat, a retired
businessman and longtime friend of President Francois Mitterrand.
   Theret was not charged with the others because he had been
hospitalized with a heart ailment. French law requires that an
investigating magistrate notify a suspect face-to-face of criminal
charges.
   Pelat and a friend, Isabelle Pierco, have been charged with
receiving insider information and profiting from it. The charge
carries the same maximum penalty as actual insider trading: two
years in prison and a fine of up to four times the amount of illegal
profits.
</TEXT>
