<DOCNO> AP890304-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 0638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     03-04 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Calls Philippines President A `Figurehead'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A founder of a leading group of
communist rebels today called President Corazon Aquino ``a
figurehead'' and claimed the military actually runs her government.
   Jose Maria Sison, co-founder of the outlawed Communist Party of
the Philippines, made his remarks in a telephone interview from the
Netherlands, where he has sought political asylum. Manila radio
station DZRH reached him at offices of the Philippine rebel National
Democratic Front in Utrecht.
   The Front is the umbrella organization for 14 Filipino Marxist
groups, including the Communist Party of the Philippines and its
military arm, the New People's Army. The rebels have been fighting
the Manila government for 20 years.
   Sison said Mrs. Aquino has a different relationship with the
country's 160,000-member armed forces than did former President
Ferdinand Marcos, who she ousted in a civilian-backed military
rebellion in February 1986.
   ``Marcos controlled and manipulated the military as an
instrument,'' Sison said. ``Mrs. Aquino, on the other hand, is being
controlled and manipulated by the military. ... Aquino is a
figurehead president.''
   Sison said Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos, a retired armed forces
chief of staff, holds sway in the military while Mrs. Aquino's
brother, Rep. Jose Cojuangco, controls ``money matters.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Col. Oscar Florendo, the armed forces spokesman who was
interviewed on the same radio program, said Sison is wrong.
   ``I think (Sison) is losing his mind,'' Florendo said. ``He has a
very rich imagination. Maybe that is the effect of the good life in
the Netherlands because he is not thinking of problems there.''
   Sison was on a speaking tour in Europe when his passport was
revoked in September by the government.
   Military officials accused Sison of engaging in subversive
activities against the government in his travels abroad. The
military has also charged that Sison had resumed his post as leader
of the clandestine Communist Party.
   Sison said nothing of his relationship to the rebel group during
his radio program. He also did not say whether Dutch authorities
have granted his application for asylum.
   Sison, who led a handful of university intellectuals in founding
the banned party in December 1968, was jailed for nearly 10 years
until Mrs. Aquino set him free.
</TEXT>
