<FIRST>r i PM-China-Bodies     03-04 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Bodies,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bodies Stack Up In Morgues Over Compensation Dispute With Relatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bodies are lying in morgues, sometimes for years,
while their survivors negotiate for money and jobs as compensation
from the dead relative's workplace, an official daily said today.
   For example, the China Daily said survivors of a worker at the
Beijing Theater Troupe have refused to let the body be cremated
until the troupe agrees to provide two apartments and a job for one
of the children.
   A second case was cited in the report of the body of a woman that
has been kept at one hospital for more than five years because the
family and her work unit can't agree on compensation.
   It also said in another hospital run by the military that 100 of
the 500 bodies in the morgue had been there more than two months.
   The daily quoted a Labor Ministry official as saying state-run
work units must pay pensions to children too young to support
themselves if their parents die or are seriously injured on the job.
   However, there are no regulations saying children can take their
parent's job, the report said.
   The official was quoted as saying, ``Chinese people are too
dependent on the government and their work units.'' He said the
Chinese ``should develop their abilities to support themselves in
society.''
</TEXT>
