<FIRST>r i India-Fire     03-04 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>India-Fire,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Complex Fire Deaths Rise To 38</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten people died today of burns suffered
when fire broke out at a parade in the steel city of Jamshedpur,
raising the death toll to 38, a news report said.
   The United News of India agency quoted hospital sources as saying
the death toll was expected to rise because 40 of the 200 people
injured had suffered burns over at least 75 percent of their bodies.
   The fire erupted Friday in a giant tent jammed with families and
executives watching celebrations at the Tata Iron and Steel Co.
complex in Jamshedpur, 140 miles west of Calcutta.
   The fire burned more than five hours before being brought under
control.
   The parade was part of the festivities marking the 150th
anniversary of the birth of Sir Jamshedji Tata, founder of an
industrial empire that encompasses steel and textile mills, bus and
truck manufacturing and a variety of other enterprises including
telephones, watches and cosmetics.
</TEXT>
