<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Botha     03-04 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Botha,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convalescing President Vows To Complete Term Of Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha says he is
determined to serve out the rest of his current term despite
``derision and attacks'' following his stroke.
   The 73-year-old Botha, in an interview published today by major
Afrikaans-language newspapers, said it was too early to speculate
whether he would seek another term after his five-year term expires
in September. He plans to return to work in April.
   Botha suffered a stroke on Jan. 18 and has spent most of the time
since then recuperating at his coastal vacation home while his
duties are carried out by an acting president, Constitutional
Development Minister Chris Heunis.
   Botha said in the interview he would complete the term despite
calls for him to step aside.
   ``The fact that I am still subject to derision and attacks shows
that I am in the way of some people,'' he was quoted as saying. ``I
have a task to perform and as my strength increases I will proceed
with that task.''
   Calls from his resignation have come from liberal and far-right
opposition parties, as well as from some members of his National
Party. A former Cabinet minister, Hendrik Schoeman, said at a
National Party rally Wednesday that Botha should make way for F.W.
Klerk, who took over as party leader a month ago and is heir
apparent for the presidency.
   Schoeman ``has said out loud what all other Nationalists are
thinking: President Botha must go _ now,'' Business Day, a leading
financial newspaper, said Friday in an editorial.
   Although de Klerk shares Botha's views on most major policy
issues, he has been depicted as more flexible. During Botha's
convalescence, both de Klerk and Heunis have suggested in speeches
that the government is willing to lessen its reliance on racial
classification as the foundation for political and social structures.
   However, de Klerk has told white voters he will not betray them
and has affirmed his commitment to segregated residential areas for
whites who want them. Like Botha, de Klerk has given no indication
he is willing to consider full voting rights for the country's black
majority.
</TEXT>
