<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Lithuania     03-04 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Lithuania,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Group Pulls Own Candidates to Boost Reform Communists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent Lithuanian group has withdrawn two
candidates for a new Soviet congress in an effort to improve the
chances of Communist Party reformers running for election, a group
spokesman said today.
   The move by the independent organization, known as Sajudis,
leaves Lithuanian Party leader Algirdas Brazauskas and his top
deputy, Vladimir Beriozov, unopposed in the March 26 elections, said
group spokesman Alvydas Medalinskas in a telephone interview from
Vilnius.
   He said Sajudis wanted to bolster the reformers' chances against
what he called ``Stalinist'' officials in a split developing in the
republic's Communist Party.
   The spokesman said Sajudis candidates Algimontas Nasvitis and
Alvydas Yozaitis withdrew from the race, part of the Soviet Union's
first national multi-candidate elections, ``for the good of
Lithuania.''
   Brazauskas has been popular in the western Baltic Republic since
he appeared at meetings of Sajudis and returned the cathedral in
Vilnius to the Roman Catholic Church.
   Medalinskas said Brazauskas faces a challenge from Jonus
Guryatskas, secretary of the Lithuanian Supreme Soviet, who led a
strong attack on Sajudis in a recent meeting of the policy-making
party committee.
   He said Sajudis candidates Algimontas Nasvitis and Alvydas
Yozaitis withdrew from the race, part of the Soviet Union's first
national multi-candidate elections, ``for the good of Lithuania.''
   The independent group will continue to run its own candidates
against Communist Party officials in almost all of Lithuania's 44
electoral districts, Medalinskas said.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, Sajudis and other
independent groups have blossomed in the three Soviet Baltic
republics, which include Estonia and Latvia. The groups are pushing
for greater autonomy from Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
