<FIRST>r i PM-Switzerland-Charles     03-04 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Switzerland-Charles,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Prince Charles Hasn't Learned From Skiing Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Swiss Ski Federation official
has accused Prince Charles of being reckless by skiing off marked
trails where a year ago an avalanche killed a close friend of the
heir to the British throne.
   The official made the accusation after a newspaper printed a
photograph purportedly showing Charles skiing in a restricted area
on Mount Gotschna near warning signs printed in four languages,
including English.
   ``There are those who learn from a mistake and there are others
who don't. Wednesday's front-page picture shows clearly that neither
the prince nor his entourage heed the warnings of the responsible
local officials,'' Sepp Scheibert said in a letter published today
in the newspaper Blick.
   Scheibert, chief of the federation's mass sports section,
stressed in his letter to the mass circulation paper that the
prince's group also was off trails when an avalanche killed a former
queen's aide, Maj. Hugh Lindsay, 34, and broke both legs of another
member of the party, Patricia Palmer-Tomkinson.
   In addition, Scheibert wrote, the Davos Institute for Avalanche
Research said snow conditions on the day the photograph was taken
were ``identical with those prevailing a year ago when the killer
avalanche struck.''
   ``What can the local officials do when such an `illustrious'
party ignores all rules and recommendations?'' he asked.
   Such conduct ``turns to ridicule all advisory bodies,'' he said.
   Charles, 40, arrived at Klosters on Monday for a skiing vacation
at the resort where the tragedy occurred March 10, 1988.
   He narrowly escaped injury on that day when the avalanche roared
down on a group of skiers he was leading on a steep run off marked
trails.
   Swiss authorities ruled the six-member group caused the avalanche
but that nobody could be held personally responsible.
   Mrs. Palmer-Tomkinson's husband, Charles, who was with the skiing
party in 1988, also accompanied the prince this year.
   The group has been reported skiing mostly on a face of the
8,000-foot Mount Gotschna, several miles south of the site of the
earlier avalanche.
</TEXT>
