<FIRST>u i PM-SatanicVerses 2ndLd-Writethru   03-04 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satanic Verses, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0481,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says Novel Offended Islam, Iran Notes Her `Sympathy'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with British official supporting
Rushdie, Iranian response. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government today reaffirmed its support
for author Salman Rushdie and warned that continued agitation over
his novel ``The Satanic Verses'' could do serious harm.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said he understood ``the hurt and
insult being felt'' by Moslems over the book but said most Britons
accept ``that in a free country people have the right of freedom of
expression.''
   Rushdie, 41, who was born a Moslem in India, has been in hiding
since Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini ordered his death on Feb.
14 and Iranian clergy offered a bounty of up to $5.2 million for the
killing.
   Hurd spoke to reporters at a local government conference of the
governing Conservative Party. It came one day after Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher said she believes the novel has deeply offended
Islam.
   Earlier today, Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said
that Mrs. Thatcher's comment was ``the first expression of sympathy
with Moslems over the book.'' Later today, Tehran Radio released a
lengthy commentary saying Mrs. Thatcher's acknowledgement must be
followed up ``with concrete actions.''
   If Britain accepts that the book is insulting, the state-run
radio said, it ``cannot object to the death sentence on the writer,
which has been issued in line with Sharia (Islamic law).''
   The radio called on Mrs. Thatcher's government to clarify
``whether or not freedom of expression and writing can be a license
for defamation and insult.'' ``If the British government does not
see the freedom of expression as a license for defamation, then
legal prosecution of the author, prevention of further publication
of the book, and removing already published copies are reasonable
requests which can remove much of the friction (in the present
situation),'' Tehran Radio said in a report monitored in Cyprus.
   Iran's Parliament said on Tuesday it would cut diplomatic ties
with Britain in a week unless it disavows the contents of Rushdie's
novel, which has been held as blasphemous by Moslem protesters
around the world.
   Britain insists Khomeini withdraw the death sentence on Rushdie,
who is now a naturalized Briton. Rushdie telephoned a parliamentary
aide on Friday to express concern that Britain was backing down in
its support for him.
   Asked whether the government was changing its attitude to
Rushdie, Hurd said: ``There's no vacillation. Let's for heaven sake
let the thing settle. Let's not keep the agitation going. It could
do serious harm.''
   IRNA also said Mrs. Thatcher's statement was ``a clear attempt to
defuse the row between Britain and Iran before next Tuesday's
deadline that the Iranian Parliament gave to London to alter its
attitude or face the consequences of a complete cut in diplomatic
ties.''
   The dispute has led the 12-member European Economic Community and
several other countries to withdraw their ambassadors from Iran.
   In Halifax in northern England, about 80 teen-agers broke away
Friday from an anti-Rushdie demonstration by 1,600 people and
damaged several cars, police said. A policeman fell and bruised his
leg, they said.
   Moslems who organized the protest immediately apologized and
offered to pay for any damage, police said.
   One death was reported Friday in clashes between police and
anti-Rushdie protests in the northern Indian city of Srinagar.
Police reportedly fired on Moslem demonstrators, killing at least
one person and injuring more than 100.
   Eighteen other people have been killed in protests over the book
in India and Pakistan.
   Demonstrations by Moslems occurred today in Bangladesh where
about 400 people marched through Dhaka shouting ``Death To Salman
Rushdie!'' and in Thailand, where about 700 protesters in Bangkok
burned an effigy of Rushdie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
