<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Laos-USMIAs     03-04 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laos-US MIAs,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laos Postpones U.S. MIA Excavation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laos put on hold today a scheduled joint
excavation with the United States to search for remains of missing
American soldiers, a U.S. diplomat in Bangkok said.
   Fourteen U.S. experts were to fly to Laos aboard two C-130
transport planes this morning, but Vientiane did not give the planes
clearance to enter Laotian airspace, said U.S. Embassy spokesman
Ross Petzing.
   He refused to speculate on the Laotians' possible reasons.
   Laos officials may have been angered when President Bush on
Wednesday recommended to Congress that the country and its neighbor,
Burma, be declared ineligible for U.S. aid because of alleged
support for drug trafficking.
   The recommendations came in an annual report Secretary of State
James Baker III sent to Congress. It said U.S. officials believe
opium production is expanding in Laos and could be approaching 300
tons a year, and that heroin is being refined there for export
through Thailand, Vietnam and China.
   U.S. officials say there is evidence that Laotian officials are
involved in processing and smuggling drugs. When that charge
surfaced in last year's narcotics report to Congress, the Laotian
government issued a stern denial.
   The United States is trying to account for 547 Americans listed
as missing in action in Laos during the U.S.-Vietnam war. Most were
airmen who flew reconnaissance and bombing missions.
   Laos had conducted four joint excavations with the United States.
The first one was in February 1985.
   The Pentagon said the latest excavation was to be in southern
Savannakhet province, where a U.S.-Laotian team surveyed in
December. The United States has no record of a U.S. plane crashing
in the area. Petzing said the U.S. team had planned to work in Laos
for eight to 10 days.
</TEXT>
