<FIRST>r i AM-LoveStory     03-04 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Love Story,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Husband of Greek Cypriot to be Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young Turkish settler who crossed
illegally into southern Cyprus to find his Greek Cypriot wife will
be deported, police said Saturday.
   The 17-year-old husband, Cengis Ciskun Seytan, was arrested last
week after slipping through the fortified no-man's-land separating
Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus from the Greek Cypriot southern
sector.
   ``It's been decided that he should be deported to Turkey and not
prosecuted here,'' Larnaca police chief Anastasis Prastitis said.
   Last summer, Seytan married 15-year-old Alexia Chronia, whose
family belongs to a dwindling community of about 1,000 Greek
Cypriots living in the Karpas district of northern Cyprus.
   The wedding received much publicity.
   Greek Cypriot authorities claimed Miss Chronia had been abducted,
forcibly converted to Islam and forced to marry Seytan.
   But U.N. officials who investigated said the teen-ager, who had
attended high school in the Greek Cypriot sector, denied she was
kidnapped and claimed she was in love with Seytan.
   Last month, however, she returned to the south declaring she had
been forced to marry Seytan and that he had threatened to harm her
parents if she refused.
   After hearing that Seytan had come south to find her, the bride
again changed her story.
   ``I love Cengis, but my family forced me to say I was kidnapped
to cover up the shame of my conversion to Islam,'' she said.
   Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded the north of the island following an Athens-inspired coup
aimed at union with Greece.
   Seytan is one of about 50,000 Turkish settlers brought to
northern Cyprus to boost the area's Turkish Cypriot minority.
</TEXT>
