<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Decepticons Bjt   03-04 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Decepticons, Bjt,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shadowy Youth Gang Comes To Symbolize NYC Street Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City high school students are taking lessons in
fear these days, and their teachers are the Decepticons _ a loosely
organized gang of young thugs who have assumed near-mythical status.
   While the gang, which preys largely on fellow teen-agers, is
responsible for only a small part of youth crime in the city,
educators say its impact goes far beyond its reality.
   ``The idea of the Decepticons has a lot of power over the kids.
It's a symbol of something bad. Like, `the boogey man is coming, the
Decepticons are coming,''' said Patricia Black, formerly a Bronx
principal and now the superintendent of Manhattan high schools.
   The drug rings that have gradually replaced most of the city's
old neighborhood-based youth gangs are more violent and make a lot
more money. But the ``Decepts,'' who emerged about three years ago
and named themselves after a group of cartoon characters, have
gained a unique hold on the imagination of high school students as a
horde of rowdies preying on easy victims near schools, taking
anything from earrings to expensive sneakers.
   Black said the mere rumor that the Decepticons were going to
invade her South Bronx high school a couple of years ago brought the
police out and prompted many parents to keep their children at home.
The Decepts failed to show up; in fact, they've never been known to
actually invade a school building.
   A group of students leaving the Park West High School on
Manhattan's West Side several days ago all knew of the Decepticons'
reputation and said many teen-agers feared them.
   ``They steal bus passes, sneakers, gold jewelry, anything,'' said
one boy who declined to give his name. But he and the other youths
said they had never actually encountered the Decepticons and knew no
one who had.
   There are 56 known members of the Decepticons, including 14 girls
who call themselves Deceptinets, police said. Gang members, who come
from all over the city and range in age from 15 to 22, typically
hang out near a school during lunch breaks or after classes and
occasionally mug a vulnerable youngster.
   They generally gather first at a Brooklyn high school and then
commute to Manhattan where they can seek victims around several high
schools along the East Side or West Side subway lines, said Edward
Muir, head of the United Federation of Teachers safety committee.
   The Decepticons have attained their notoriety largely because
``they're the only game in town,'' Muir said. Drug rings, with their
tremendous profits, lure most of the youths who would have been
drawn to the old-style gangs and their turf battles, authorities say.
   ``You can certainly make a lot more money by selling drugs to
kids than by stealing their sneakers,'' Muir said.
   During the early 1970s, the city had some 400 youth gangs with
nearly 20,000 members. The police now know of 37 gangs with about
1,000 members, said Sgt. John Galea, head of the police department's
youth gang intelligence unit.
   The Decepticons, named for fiendish, missile-hurling cartoon
characters on television's ``The Transformers,'' are the largest and
by far the most notorious of the remaining youth gangs.
   The Decepts wear no insignia or gang colors and dress like many
other teens in designer clothes, expensive leather basketball shoes
and lots of gold jewelry. They dress like other city youngsters,
Galea explained, ``because they steal the other kids' clothes.''
   They arm themselves with ax handles, hammers, box cutters,
occasionally knives, but they rarely carry guns, Galea said. Almost
exclusively, their victims are their peers.
   Five Decepticons were arrested on assault charges last year, and
gang members were charged in 43 robberies, mostly involving thefts
of clothing and jewelry, police said.
   The reality of the gang is that it exists. The mythology is that
it is everywhere in large numbers, Galea said: ``We have reports
that they're going to invade schools in Manhattan, the Bronx,
Queens, all in the same day.''
   Galea says the Decepticons are responsible for only a ``very,
very small portion of youth crime.''
   But the gang has a strong hold on the imaginations of many
students who use the term ``Decepts'' for any group of violent teens.
   ``Their name is by far the most infamous; it does elicit fear,''
Galea said. ``As the kids travel throughout the city, this is the
name they hear.''
</TEXT>
