<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-04 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DONALDSONVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Woo, woo, woo! It's almost time for da
Shemp Festival. Dat's Shemp, as in Larry, Moe an' Coiley, but widout
dem udda guys.
   The Fifth Annual Shemp Festival, March 18 and 19 this year,
celebrates the birthday of what organizers call the most forgotten
of the Three Stooges.
   Highlights include a pie fight with 1,000 specially baked pies.
   And then there's the crowning at the 1989 Pie Queen at the Shemp
Festival Banquet.
   ``The festival committee will be looking for the most upper
crust, snooty socialite hag who degenerates into the most low-down,
disgusting hedonistic slime,'' said Kirk Landry, one of three
friends who dreamed up the festival. ``You also get bonus points for
trying to bribe Senior Festival Committee members with sexual
favors.''
   Shemp, actually Sam Horwitz, was born March 17, 1895. He and Ted
Healy organized the trio of Shemp, his brother Moe and Larry Fine.
Shemp left the group in 1934, was replaced by his brother Curley,
rejoined in 1946 and died in 1955.
   ``They were great comics,'' Landry said. ``Everybody can identify
with them.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Say you get an envelope in the mail and you
want to see if it's a bill or a notice that you've won a $1 million
sweepstakes before ripping it open. Or you're curious about the
plain brown wrapper addressed to your teen-aged son.
   Sharper Image, the retailer of high-tech toys for grown-ups, is
selling a $39, 3{-ounce spray that turns a thick manila envelope
transparent, allowing the user to read what's inside.
   The X-Ray Spray, on the market for two weeks, begins to evaporate
within 30 seconds and leaves no indication the envelope has been
altered. The manufacturer says the liquid is nontoxic, nonflammable
and won't smear ink.
   No sales figures were available, but ``we've sold quite a few
though _ mostly to people who want to use it as a joke,'' said Anne
McCamman, a sales clerk at Sharper Image's store on Market Street.
   Joke or not, not everyone's amused.
   ``I don't want to call anyone slimy, but why would you need this
spray for anything but reading someone else's mail?'' asked Postal
Service inspector C.W. Lawrence in Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHAZY LANDING, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a new face among the cows in
the feedlot at Robert Gravelle's farm.
   A 500-pound elk joined the herd last November and Gravelle's
family named her Elsie and kept quiet about her until hunting season
was over.
   Elsie's not a secret anymore, but no one in this Lake Champlain
town near the Canadian border can figure out where she came from.
   ``Once we saw her coming out of the water, coming out of the
lake,'' Gravelle said. ``That kind of makes me think she came from
Vermont. She might have crossed the lake.''
   Lake Champlain separates New York from Vermont.
   Wildlife officials say Elsie probably escaped from captivity, but
so far no one has reported her missing. A tag in the animal's ear
carries a number, but no information about her home.
   Whatever her origin, Elsie should be safe among Gravelle's cows.
   ``If anyone even looks at her the wrong way, they could be in big
trouble,'' said Lt. Charles Reynolds of the state Department of
Environmental Conservation. ``There is no open season on elk in New
York state, so elk cannot be hunted.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana University-Purdue University at
Indianapolis is a mouthful for the name of a campus and its initials
aren't much better _ IUPUI _ but what else can you call it?
   The school's External Affairs Coordinating Council consulted with
various advertising agencies in Indianapolis and hired a researching
company to conduct a study.
   They conducted polls and studies, but couldn't come up with a
suitable new name, the council reported Thursday.
   The study can be traced to IU President Thomas Ehrlich, who asked
IUPUI faculty members if they were bothered that their campus was
nicknamed ``ooey-pooey.''
