<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-PrisonPlot     03-04 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Prison Plot,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Neo-Fascists Arrested in Prison Break Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Saturday they arrested three members
of a right-wing terror group in connection with a plot to stage a
prison break at a maximum-security prison.
   Police said the three were arrested Thursday afternoon when they
claimed a suitcase at a suburban train station that contained a
submachine gun, a pistol, ammunition, police uniforms and fake
Italian army license plates.
   Italian news agencies said police identified the trio as Antonio
D'Inzillo, Gianluca Ponzio and Giorgio de Angelis, all 26 and all
from Rome. Police said they are members of the Armed Revolutionary
Nucleus terror group.
   Three other people were arrested Feb. 18 in connection with the
planned break from Rebibbia prison.
   Police said one of the three arrested in February, Luca Onesti,
33, tried to swallow a piece of paper that contained details of the
plot.
   Authorities said the note outlined a plan to conceal explosives
inside cakes and smuggle them into certain inmates at the prison,
which is on the outskirts of Rome.
   The plot was reportedly aimed at freeing some prisoners with
rightist sympathies and some imprisoned for violent crimes. It did
not say how many inmates were supposed to be freed.
