<DOCNO> AP890304-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Beckett Bjt   03-04 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Beckett, Bjt,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Samuel Beckett Emerges from Silence with Meditation on Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his 83rd year, Samuel Beckett has emerged from a
studied silence with a brief novella, a meditation on old age that a
reviewer praised as ``another of Beckett's nihilistic mantras, best
mumbled aloud.''
   Only 200 copies of ``Stirrings Still,'' the 1,801-word new work
by the Nobel Prize-winning author of ``Waiting for Godot,'' are
being printed. They are offered for sale at $1,720 each.
   ``The way they've gone this morning, they'll be gone by next
week,'' publisher John Calder said Friday, after the entire novella
was published in The Guardian newspaper.
   The signed, limited edition includes illustrations by the Irish
artist Louis LeBrocquy, who also illustrated an edition of James
Joyce's ``Dubliners,'' Calder said. A mass-market edition will be
published, he said, but not for a couple of years.
   Calder said ``Stirrings Still'' was written in response to pleas
from Beckett's American publisher, Barney Rossett, formerly of Grove
Press Inc., though there are no immediate plans to print it in the
United States.
   It is a tale, reviewer Frank Kermode wrote in The Guardian, that
is typical Beckett _ ``of a featureless man in a virtually
featureless world, expressing a condition in which everything that
characterizes some of our normal assumptions about human existence
... is virtually annulled, in prose rich only its unmatched
parsimony.''
   Given the price, Kermode said, ``purchasers can henceforth
meditate the destitution of their existence and simultaneously take
pleasure in their privilege.''
   This paragraph is typical of the style of the opus:
   ``A clock afar struck the hours and half-hours. The same as when
among others Darly once died and left him. Strokes now clear as if
carried by a wind now faint on the still air. Cries afar now faint
now clear. Head on hands half hoping when the hour struck that the
half-hour would not and half fearing that it would not. Similarly
when the half-hour struck. Similarly when the cries a moment ceased.
Or merely wondering. Or merely waiting. Waiting to hear.''
   Born in Dublin and educated at Trinity College, Cambridge,
Beckett went to Paris in 1928 and became acquainted with James
Joyce, the Irish novelist and poet who became the subject of
Beckett's first published essay a year later.
   Beckett eventually decided to live in France, saying he preferred
``France in war to Ireland in peace.'' He has continued to live in
France, writing both in French and English.
   His last work, Calder said, was a novella titled ``Worstword Ho''
in 1982.
   ``Stirrings Still'' is hardly Beckett's most concise work.
``Breath,'' a 1969 theater piece, consisted of a pile of rubbish, a
breath and a cry, lasting no more than 30 seconds.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890304-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InterstatePileup     03-04 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Interstate Pileup,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Dead In Chain Collision Caused By Blowing Dust, Unknown Motorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOWIE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorist who stopped on a highway during a
blinding dust storm is believed to have started a chain reaction
collision of 31 vehicles in which three people were killed, police
said.
   At least 40 people were injured.
   The motorist who stopped in a traffic lane on Interstate 10 in
southeastern Arizona was not involved in the accident, and drove
away before anyone recorded his license number, the state Department
of Public Safety said.
   Officer Dick Pittman said eight tractor-trailer rigs, a Greyhound
bus and 22 cars were involved in the accident in the middle of the
afternoon Friday.
   ``It was total black. You couldn't see the road,'' said Lee Host,
of Chicago, the driver of a tractor-trailer rig that struck the
Greyhound bus. He suffered only a bruised arm.
   Wreckage was still being cleared away Saturday.
   The entire front of the bus, en route from Phoenix to El Paso,
Texas, was sheared off when it collided with another vehicle after
being struck from the rear by Host's truck.
   ``You don't have no protection up there (in the driver's seat),''
said bus driver J.D. Black, 43. ``It's just fiberglass and thin
metal. I'm very glad to be alive.''
   Black, of Phoenix, said most of his 25 passengers were treated
for minor injuries. A bus official said a pregnant woman was
admitted to a hospital for observation.
   Rik Wilson, 36, was on his way from California to New Mexico in
his new pickup. He said he saw a jackknifed tractor-trailer on the
road in front of him, and started pulling off toward a ditch on the
left.
   ``Then I looked in the rear-view mirror and saw a bus skidding
toward me,'' he said. ``I opened the door to get away. I was just
out the door when the bus hit my truck.''
   ``If I had been in the vehicle, my head would have gone right
through the windshield,'' Wilson said.
   At least two of the dead were believed to be out-of-state
truckers, Pittman said. The injured were taken to hospitals in
Willcox, Benson and Tucson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
