<FIRST>r a AM-People     03-04 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0929</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was about the time someone started
pouring sand from an ashtry on top of his head that combative
television talk-show host Morton Downey Jr. realized something was
wrong.
   Downey, 55, had already allowed a performance artist to wrap a
telephone cord around his neck, but executive producer Bill Boggs
said he decided to stop taping the show Friday when the artist began
showering Downey with sand.
   The artist, Mark Kostabi, 30, also threw paint on a studio camera
as part of the show on ``Artists Defending Their Art.''
   ``It's a case of an artist I think starting out thinking he's
doing something funny (but) really hurting people.'' Boggs said.
``Everything was under control except that he (Kostabi) hurt Mort.''
   Downey injured his right thumb as he helped security guards
remove Kostabi from the WWOR studio, and was treated and released
from the Meadowlands Hospital Medical Center, Boggs said.
   Boggs said Kostabi later telephoned the show and offered to pay
for the camera. Kostabi has an unlisted phone number and could not
be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIAN WELLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Today'' show co-host Bryant Gumbel,
taking part in a golf tournament in this desert resort near Palm
Springs, declined to comment on the furor over his criticism of most
of the show's personalities.
   ``Not a chance, not a chance,'' Gumbel said Friday when asked to
comment on reaction to his comments about ``Today'' show staffers.
   The memo, written last August by Gumbel to ``Today'' Executive
Producer Marty Ryan, spared Gumbel's co-host, Jane Pauley, but
berated the work of consumer affairs reporter David Horowitz, movie
critic Gene Shalit and weatherman Willard Scott.
   While Shalit and Horowitz dismissed the complaints, Scott told
the nationally syndicated Entertainment Tonight program that he
might not be able to remain with ``Today'' if he and Gumbel cannot
reach a reconciliation.
   Ms. Pauley said the incident is best forgotten, however.
   ``This is not a national crisis,'' she told Entertainment Tonight
in an interview broadcast Friday. ``Sure it was a problem, but every
family has its ups and downs.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WATERVILLE VALLEY, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 250 people turned out to
greet Vice President Dan Quayle as has arrived in New Hampshire for
a weekend of skiing in the White Mountains.
   Quayle, accompanied by his wife and two of his children, shook
hands and joked with the crowd upon his arrival at Laconia Airport
Friday afternoon.
   The vice president told reporters he considers himself a moderate
but aggressive skier who is improving.
   Quayle and John Sununu, the White House chief of staff and former
New Hampshire governor, are joining other politicians and
celebrities for the Governor's Ski Invitational.
   Sununu organized the second annual event, which benefits the
Christa McAuliffe Sabbatical Trust, established in memory of the
Concord teacher who died in the 1986 space shuttle disaster.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music performer Naomi Judd, the
elder half of the mother-daughter duo the Judds, plans to marry a
former Elvis Presley background singer in early May, a spokesman
says.
   Judd and Larry Strickland are working out details of the
ceremony, said Chuck Thompson, publicist for the singer.
   Judd, 43, a former nurse, was divorced in 1977 from her first
husband.
   Strickland is a gospel music singer who has been a member of the
Stamps Quartet, which was Elvis Presley's background vocal group in
the 1970s.
   Judd and daughter Wynonna are known for their hit records
``Grandpa,'' ``Mama He's Crazy'' and ``Change of Heart.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a decade as president of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, Paul E. Gray is expected to become chairman
of its governing board in July 1990.
   Gray, a 57-year-old specialist in electronic circuits and
semiconductors, will be nominated to succeed David S. Saxon as
chairman of the MIT Corporation, the institute said Friday. Saxon,
69, said he plans to retire.
   In recent years, Gray has pushed the institute toward greater
introspection, particularly on the issues of racial tolerance on
campus and the role of science in society. MIT is currently
evaluating its curriculum to strengthen its instruction in the
humanities.
   Except for two years of military service from 1955-57, Gray has
been associated with MIT since he entered as a freshmen in 1950. He
served as a professor, dean of the school of engineering and
chancellor efore assuming the presidency in 1980.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer La Toya Jackson said she is not the
same performer as her brother, Michael, although everyone else seems
to want her to be.
   ``I'm not Michael. I can't be him. I'm La Toya,'' she said during
a promotional appearance Friday in Dallas. ``I have to give them
what I can do.''
   ``A lot of artists follow whatever he does: He sets the pattern
and they go in that direction. But as far as I'm concerned, I'm
going to set my own patterns.''
   Ms. Jackson was promoting a new record album called ``La Toya
Jackson.'' She also plans a book on her family and to begin
recording another album in April.
   Ms. Jackson, who recently made a swing of national talk shows
following a photo layout in Playboy, was asked about rumors that she
has undergone plastic surgery.
   ``If I'd had it, the pictures would have looked a lot better,
believe me.''
</TEXT>
