<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-DetroitJOA     03-04 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Detroit JOA,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspaper Merger Blocked by Supreme Court Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice on Saturday blocked, at
least until March 17, the partial merger of Detroit's two daily
newspapers that was to begin Monday.
   Justice William J. Brennan, in an unexpected move, said the
Detroit Free Press and The Detroit News may not start the partial
merger until the full Supreme Court considers the issue at its next
regularly scheduled closed-door conference, March 17.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist on Friday had refused to
postpone the partial merger, and lawyers for opponents to the deal
then turned to Brennan for help.
   Reporters initially had been told that Brennan was not going to
act on the emergency request before Monday.
   A federal appeals court panel here voted 2-1 to uphold
then-Attorney General Edwin Meese's decision to allow the Detroit
papers to form a joint operating agreement under the federal
Newspaper Preservation Act.
   The 1970 law empowers the attorney general to give financially
failing newspapers an exemption from antitrust laws.
   Under the joint operating agreement, the two Detroit newspapers
would combine their business, advertising and production departments
but maintain separate news and editorial staffs.
   By a 5-4 vote last month, the full appeals court refused to
reconsider the three-judge panel's Jan. 27 ruling. The appeals court
blocked the partial merger until March 6 so opponents could seek a
longer delay from Rehnquist.
   That delay was denied Friday.
   But Brennan, in a three-paragraph order issued Saturday, said he
was referring the matter to the full court.
   His order added, ``It is further ordered that the order staying
implementation of the joint operating agreement issued ... by the
(appeals court) is continued pending further order of the court.''
   A group of Michigan readers and advertisers who sued to stop the
partial merger contend that the Free Press, a morning newspaper
owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., is not a failing newspaper even though
it lost $10 million a year between 1981 and 1986.
   The opponents, calling themselves Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press, say the Free Press and News, which lost $50
million in the same period, were unprofitable solely because both
papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out
of business.
   Gannett Co., which owns the News, is the nation's largest
newspaper publishing group. Knight-Ridder is the second largest.
   Knight-Ridder has threatened to close down the Free Press if the
joint operating agreement is not approved.
   The opponents' emergency request said the agreement ``threatens
the independence of daily newspapers in 25 cities'' where, like
Detroit, competing newspapers still exist.
   The case is Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press. vs.
Thornburgh, A-695.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890304-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-TrainWreck 6thWritethru a0536 03-04 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Train Wreck, 6th Writethru, a0536,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Trains Collide Outside London Killing Up To 12 People</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphc NY23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with as many as 12 dead. Pickup
8th graf pvs, ``A spokesman...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two passenger trains collided outside London today
in an accident that killed up to 12 people, injured about 50 and
sent carriages careening into the gardens of trackside homes,
authorities and witnesses said.
   Authorities said one train hit the back of the other near the
Purley station in Surrey, on the southern outskirts of the capital.
   One train remained on the track but seven cars from the other
fell down an embankment into the gardens, the Fire Brigade said.
   There was no indication anyone was hurt in the houses, but
firefighters had to cut dozens of passengers free from the wreckage.
   There were conflicting casualty reports.
   About five hours after the 1:39 p.m. crash, the emergency room
chief at nearby Mayday Hospital, Kambiz Hashemi, said four people
died there and six at the scene. The bodies of two women were
reported at nearby St. Helier Hospital, but it was not clear whether
they were included among those dead at the scene.
   The Fire Brigade and British Rail said two people died. Fire
officials put the injury toll at 50. British Rail said 32 people
were injured.
   A spokesman for British Rail Southern Region said it appeared
that one train, traveling north to London from Horsham, West Sussex,
had been crossing from the local line to a fast track when it
collided with a train bound for London from Littlehampton, on the
south coast of England.
   ``We presume at this stage that the other (Littlehampton) train
was already on the fast lane but we do not know how they impacted,''
the spokesman said.
   On Dec. 12, a three-train crash near London's Clapham Junction
station, 10 miles to the north of today's accident, killed 35
people. Railroad officials blamed malfunctioning signals for that
crash.
   In today's accident, one train ran into the back of another,
plowed to one side, and slid down the steep embankment, Fire Brigade
divisional officer Ian Park said. Seven carriages ``slid away and
turned over,'' he said.
   Samantha Muggeridge, 16, who was waiting on the Purley platform,
said: ``A slow train was coming toward Purley station. A faster one
came up behind it and seemed to clip the back of it.
   ``Three carriages from the first train rolled down the embankment
and others stayed on the tracks but they were twisted and tilted.
   ``There was a very loud crash after the collision followed by an
eerie silence. Then doors of the train started to open and there
were shouts from inside the carriages.''
   People ran from their homes and helped evacuate some of the
injured. Other injured made their own way to safety, some apparently
driven to hospital by a man who had his car parked in the street.
   Ambulance crews raced to the scene and hospitals went on alert.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was ``very distressed'' to hear
of the train crash and was being kept informed of developments, said
a spokesman for her 10 Downing St. office.
   A public inquiry is currently under way into a Dec. 12 crash.
   State-run British Rail has blamed its own flawed system in
installing new signaling equipment for the crash.
   Railway officials believe malfunctioning signals led one commuter
train to slam into the rear of another that was stopped on the
tracks. An empty freight train on an adjacent line then plowed into
the wreckage and apparently hit some passengers who had scrambled
onto the tracks.
   The Clapham crash was the worst train wreck in Britain since
1975, when 43 people died in a subway train that crashed in a London
tunnel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
