<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Strike     03-04 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Strike,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Occupy Hospitals Where Workers Are On Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of police occupied hospitals
in the country's four main cities on Saturday to keep regular
medical services running during a five-day strike by hospital
workers.
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo sent police armed with tear gas and
M-16 rifles into the hospitals late Friday and ordered 4,000 nurses,
cooks and administrators to return to work by Monday or lose their
jobs. No violence was reported.
   ``Our purpose is to open the hospitals so that the employee who
wants to work can do so,'' Azcona Hoyo said Friday. ``The ones who
don't do it will be sanctioned or fired and immediately replaced by
someone who wants to work for the benefit of the people.''
   He said the strikers, who are demanding higher wages, were
``violating the constitution by not attending to the public health.''
   He and Public Health Minister Ramon Villeda Bermudez said the
workers would lose their jobs if the strike did not end by Monday
morning.
   Celeo Alvarez Casildo, president of the Medical and Hospital
Workers' Union, said the strike would continue. Since Tuesday,
employees have been giving only emergency care while hundreds of
people wait outside for non-emergency attention.
   ``We will continue defending our rights to the end,'' he said.
``The government promised to increase our salaries ... and it
tricked us.''
   Workers are demanding salary increases totaling $2.6 million
annually. The average Honduran hospital worker earns about $200 a
month.
   The health minister said the government can only give the workers
annual total increases of $1.5 million ``because of the grave
economic crisis facing Honduras.''
   He said the medical workers have declared some 36 strikes in the
past two years to demand what he called ``exaggerated'' salary
increases.
</TEXT>
