<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Scene Bjt   03-04 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Scene, Bjt,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Paralyzes Eastern Operations at Atlanta</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AX4, AX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' jets sat idle in the fog at the
nation's second-busiest airfield Saturday _ but not because of the
weather.
   Striking mechanics virtually paralyzed Eastern Airlines here, and
normally bustling concourses were vacant except for pickets and
clusters of frustrated fliers.
   Many would-be passengers were trying to get to Miami for
connections to the Caribbean, where they had paid reservations on
cruise ships. Others were students heading for warmer climes over
spring break.
   Eastern, which handles about a third of the traffic through
Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport, originally had 278
departures scheduled for Saturday. By noon, only two planes had
left, both for Miami. One Eastern flight had arrived.
   Planes from other airlines roared on and off the runways, past
row on row of Eastern jets sitting idle.
   Airport spokesman John Braden said the effect of the heavy fog,
which could have backed up departing flights, was lessened because
of the canceled Eastern flights.
   But that was no comfort to the passengers holding Eastern
tickets. In the terminal, some played cards to pass the time while
others snoozed, using carry-on luggage for pillows. Many complained
they weren't told of flight cancellations until the last minute.
   ``I was on the phone with Eastern every day since Monday, and
they kept telling me, `It's going to fly, it's going to fly,''' said
Dick Tunner of Charlotte, N.C., who was scheduled to meet a cruise
ship in Jamaica with his wife, Grace, and had made his reservations
two months ago.
   ``We were on the phone three hours yesterday trying to get
through to them and when we did, they told us at 4:30 (p.m.) that
maybe it won't,'' he said.
   A frantic scramble ensued to get other tickets as far as Atlanta.
Later Saturday morning, the Tunners managed to get on one of the two
Eastern planes leaving for Miami, and were hoping they'd make it to
Jamaica.
   Tunner said he was sorry for those on strike. ``But if we miss
the ship, who's going to repay the $3,000 we paid for the cruise?''
he asked.
   It was suspenseful for the Tunners and the relatively few other
travelers who managed to get on an Eastern plane. Strikebreakers
loaded luggage onto a Boeing 727 for Flight 843, bound for Miami,
while Eastern waited to see if a crew would report. Waiting
passengers applauded when one pilot arrived.
   Later, the luggage was taken off and put on a smaller DC-9, which
requires a smaller crew. The flight finally left for Miami at 11:15
a.m., an hour and 45 minutes late, leaving many passengers behind.
   ``See you on the ship,'' one couple called to less-fortunate
friends who didn't get on board.
   ``I hope you're right,'' came the reply.
   A second flight for Miami and Jamaica left a few minutes later
with those who didn't get on board the first plane, but airport
officials said they did not know if Eastern would be able to get
more planes out after that.
   Machinists and pilots picketed outside the terminal and in
concourses where Eastern has flights. Nails were spread in an
Eastern employee parking lot overnight, Braden said, but he said
they were swept up and there was no damage.
   And most Eastern travelers were not going anywhere.
   ``Eastern was invisible,'' complained Kris Kiessel, a college
student from Greensboro, N.C., who was on her way to Bahamas with a
friend.
   ``We called and they said everything was normal,'' she said.
After the strike canceled her flight, she and her friend were able
to use their Eastern tickets to get as far as Atlanta on a Delta
flight.
   ``When we got here they said they could send us back home.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890304-0099 </DOCNO>
