<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Shields     03-04 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Shields,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Co-Founder of Older Women's League, Displaced Homemakers Alliance
Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurie Shields, a co-founder of the Older
Women's League and the Alliance for Displaced Homemakers, has died
at age 68, the league announced.
   Ms. Shields died Friday at her home in Oakland, Calif., of breast
cancer, said league spokeswoman Mary Gardner Jones.
   ``Laurie Shields was an indomitable woman who was fired by
concern for displaced homemakers and older women _ women confronted
by widowhood, divorce and sex and age discrimination,'' said Lou
Glasse, president of the Older Women's League.
   ``Women all across the country have lost a powerful force,''
Glasse said. ``She will be missed.''
   She and Tish Sommers, who died in 1985, founded the Alliance for
Displaced Homemakers in 1975 and the Older Women's League in 1980.
   Ms. Shields knew first-hand the problems experienced by both.
After her husband died in 1970 at age 71, ``she found herself unable
to get a job because of age discrimination,'' the league said in a
statement.
   The Older Women's League now has more than 17,000 members in 120
chapters nationwide, the league said.
   More recently, Ms. Shields and Ms. Sommers wrote a book called,
``Women Take Care,'' about the experience of caregivers in this
society. It was published after Ms. Sommers' death.
   During a national book tour, Ms. Shields said that the caregiving
movement should support those who choose not to be caregivers as
well as to those who do.
   ``Although I chose to be a caregiver twice ... it's not a role
that is everyone's cup of tea,'' she said. ``We must work together
to prevent society from force-feeding it to the women simply because
it is perceived to be a woman's role.
   The Chicago native had a business career in merchandising and
advertising for Lever Brothers and Dancer-Fitzgerald-Sample before
her marriage to actor Arthur Shields.
   She is survied by a daughter, Christine Shields of Oakland.
</TEXT>
