<DOCNO> AP890304-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CapGunRobber     03-04 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cap Gun Robber,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transient Held for 60 Stickups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transient was arrested for using a cap
gun to hold up more than 60 stores, police said.
   Fernando Sanchez, 34, was arrested Friday at a hotel in La Habra,
five miles north of Anaheim, and booked for investigation of
robbery. He was held Saturday on $50,000 bail.
   Thousands of dollars were taken from florists, ice cream shops,
beauty salons and other small businesses in 11 Orange County cities
since Oct. 28, said Sgt. Chet Barry. Seventeen holdups were in
Anaheim.
   The robber, nicknamed the ``bagman bandit'' because he carried a
gun in a plastic bag, sometimes robbed both a store and customers,
Barry said.
   ``I can tell you that in the Anaheim robberies, he was averaging
anywhere from $200 to $400,'' Barry said.
   Sanchez was traced through a check taken in one robbery.
Investigators found a cap pistol apparently used in the holdups,
Barry said.
   ``It was a real good replica of a .45,'' Barry said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
