<DOCNO> AP890304-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Tensions Bjt   03-04 0922</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Tensions, Bjt,0944</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor, Management Conflict Was Ready To Explode</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor-management tensions that erupted into a strike
Saturday have been building inexorably for years at Eastern
Airlines, and both sides are dug in for what could be a fight to the
end _ not just to their conflict, but to the 60-year-old airline
itself.
   ``It's a tremendously unfortunate set of circumstances that has
been developing for a while,'' said an emotional James Ashlock, an
Eastern company spokesman and lobbyist for 22 years. ``At some
point, we had to come to this.''
   Management says the company, losing more than $1 million a day,
just can't make it with its high-priced, demanding labor unions. The
workers deny that they're overpaid and say management is tearing the
company apart anyway, so they might as well stand and fight.
   ``Our people have been frustrated, they've been provoked, they've
been brutalized. They're ready for something forceful to show their
feelings,'' Charles E. Bryan, Eastern Machinists union District 100
president who joined the company as a mechanic in 1956, said before
what he predicted would be ``a wingding of a strike.''
   After a 17-month contract dispute, Eastern's largest union walked
out at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday and was quickly joined by pilots and
flight attendants. With the carrier virtually shut down, company
officials admitted they were surprised by the solidarity of the
pilots with the Machinists.
   ``I think this has been building and everybody understands the
company wants to divide the pilots and the (Machinists),'' Eastern
pilots union spokesman Ron Cole said. ``It's not a Machinists issue.
It's a Frank Lorenzo issue.''
   Bankrupting the airline ``is a very real possibility,'' Cole
said. ``But that's where the airline is headed anyway, so we can
face the music now when we have some leverage, or we can face the
music later when there's nothing left.''
   Lorenzo, the Texas Air Corp. chairman who bought Eastern three
years ago, has solidified his anti-union reputation at a carrier
that already had some of the airline industry's most recalcitrant
unions. His new management in 1987 demanded 30 percent wage
concessions it said was necessary to keep Eastern, bought on the
brink of bankruptcy with nearly $2.5 billion in debts, alive.
   The balking unions were hit with thousands of layoffs, firings
and suspensions. A flight attendant was fired after allegedly
pocketing $2 in drink money, her union said, and another was
disciplined for repeated absences after she was raped.
   Machinists' horror stories included a firing for refusing to work
overtime on Christmas, while the pilots said their ranks shrank by
more than 1,000 because of stress and forced overflying.
   The management said it was time for Eastern workers to face
reality _ they were being paid too much and were used to lax rules
that were puttin Eastern out of business.
   The company, led for more than two decades by World War I flying
ace Eddie Rickenbacker and then for a decade by Apollo 8 astronaut
Frank Borman, was slow to react to the jet age and slower still to
adjust to airline deregulation.
   Borman tried a number of innovative programs and at times seemed
a model of enlightened management in his dealings with Eastern
unions.
   But, labor leaders said, he couldn't keep his promises and
workers decided that wage givebacks they made in return for Eastern
stock and profits were going down the drain.
   ``Eastern has been a cash-flow generator for its lenders for
years, and has never been designed to make a profit,'' said Cole, an
Eastern pilot for 19 years and the son of a pilot who flew with the
airline for 38 years.
   Ashlock said the company in happier times was excessively
generous to unions that only became more militant. A major turning
point came with the 1980 election of Bryan to head the Machinists,
he said.
   Bryan, depicted by management as an ego-driven man with a
near-mad vision of running the airline himself, believes giving
employees company decision-making power improves productivity and
service. He also says the workers have more pride in Eastern than
management does.
   He has tried to organize an employee takeover of the company or
attract ``white knights'' to buy out Lorenzo. He and the other
unions have fought Lorenzo at every turn, with myriad lawsuits,
grievances and lobbying in Congress.
   But, Bryan said recently, the actions turned out to be only a
delay of the inevitable showdown as, he claimed, Lorenzo tried to
break the unions while ``cannibalizing Eastern and leaving only a
shell.''
   Texas Air made Eastern's computer reservations system a
subsidiary, reaped hundreds of millions of dollars in management
fees and loans from Eastern, and sold its profitable northeast
Shuttle service to New York developer Donald Trump, a sale that is
awaiting final federal approval.
   While Borman was able to elicit some concessions, the unions
looked at Texas Air's record and refused to give in to Lorenzo.
   He beat a strike at tiny Texas International two decades ago and
then ended a labor rebellion after his bitter takeover of
Continental by sending the carrier into bankruptcy reorganization in
1983. Labor contracts were abrogated.
   ``No one believes Frank Lorenzo will stop trying to ruin the
unions if we don't fight,'' said Mary Jane Barry, flight attendants
union president. ``At Eastern, they have continued to ask employees
to make concessions to fund mismanagement. It worked once, it worked
twice, it can't continue to work any longer.''
   ``This is really make it or break it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
