<FIRST>r a AM-FreeHome     03-04 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Free Home,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Home To Anyone Willing To Take It Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's only one catch to the free home
Robert K. Stirling is offering in central Indiana _ the new owner
has to cart away the 1,100-square-foot house with a two-car garage.
   Sterling bought the house and property for about $26,000 so he
could enlarge the medical offices of his parents, Robert and Marie
Stirling, and his sister, Nancy Stirling, who practice podiatry in a
building next door.
   ``For us to just demolish it and throw it away would cost $2,000.
Before I do that, I should see if it will work out for someone
else,'' Stirling said.
   He admitted the house needs a lot of work.
   The sagging roof needs shoring up and new shingles, and the
interior of the building has been ``stripped,'' Stirling said.
   The plain cardboard sign that has been standing since Monday has
attracted plenty of attention. Motorists drive around the block for
second peeks, and some pull up to get a closer look, he said.
   Stirling said he wants to have the house off the lot this month.
   ``We've had a lot of people ask us about it _ maybe 15 calls. So
far, there's been no firm takers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
