<FIRST>r a AM-DEAAgentFuneral     03-04 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DEA Agent Funeral,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain DEA Agent Remembered As `Non-Violent' Man</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal drug agent whose murder touched
off a nationwide manhunt was eulogized Saturday as a ``teddy bear of
a man'' who fell victim to the violence he sought to prevent.
   About 4,000 mourners turned out for the funeral of Drug
Enforcement Agency Agent Everett Hatcher of Boonton. Hatcher was
unarmed when he was shot to death Tuesday by a man whom officials
say has ties to organized crime.
   Thousands of DEA and FBI agents and policemen from as far away as
Canada lined up in the parking lot outside St. Christopher's Church
when the hearse pulled up.
   The strains of a single bagpipe from the New York Police
Department's Emerald Society pipe band cut through the chilly air
while the flag-draped coffin was carried up the steps.
   Also present at the heavily guarded, 1{-hour service were FBI
head William Sessions, DEA chief John Lawn, New York Mayor Edward I.
Koch, and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   Father Frank Ferraioli, the family priest, described Hatcher as a
gentle and kind man who would live on in the memories of those who
met him.
   ``He was not a man of violence,'' the priest said.
   A former DEA agent and close friend of Hatcher's, Joseph
DeGenaro, recalled the slain agent as a ``teddy bear of a man'' who
loved to make people laugh and whom he remembered ``grinning from
ear to ear.''
   ``He has touched all of us and we are sad he's gone,'' he said.
``But he lives on in our minds and our hearts.''
   At the service were the slain agent's wife, Maryjane Hatcher, and
the couple's two children, Joshua, 3, and Zachary, 9.
   Mrs. Hatcher said Friday that people who use drugs must share the
blame for her husband's death.
   ``Even through the grief and our loss, I must ask the question,
who really killed Everett Emerson Hatcher?'' she said. ``Who are the
ultimate guilty parties who create the market for the poison which
he valiantly tried to remove from our society?''
   DEA officials said the investigation of Hatcher's killing was
continuing ``satisfactorily.''
   A van that was driven by the main suspect, Costible Farace, 28,
of New York's Staten Island, was found late Friday in Staten Island.
   Officials believe Farace, a paroled killer, shot Hatcher four
times during a meeting in a secluded area along an expressway on
Staten Island. Hatcher, who was wearing a radio transmitter, had
previously met with Farace several times.
   The DEA has undertaken a nationwide search for Farace. He had not
been charged with murder, but a warrant was issued for his arrest on
narcotics charges.
   New York Police Department spokesman Jim Coleman said Farace
appeared to have loose ties to the Bonanno crime family, and was
involved in a ring that transported cocaine from Florida to New York.
   Stutman said officials had gotten calls from hundreds of people
trying to cooperate with the investigation, but ``as any tedious
investigation it will take time to build a case.''
   ``We will locate Mr. Farace, you can rest assured of that,'' he
said.
   Stutman has ordered New York's 500 DEA agents to focus on the
murder until Farace is found. A nationwide search was underway.
   President Bush will visit the DEA in New York this week, a visit
expected to boost what he said was low morale in the wake of the
murder, Stutman said. DEA head Lawn said Bush also planned to meet
with Hatcher's family.
</TEXT>
