<FIRST>r i AM-Mauritius     03-04 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mauritius,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mauritian Leader Reportedly Escapes Second Assassination Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT LOUIS, Mauritius (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Aneerood Jugnauth has
escaped the second assassination attempt in four months, local
newspapers reported Saturday.
   Police said they arrested a man who tried to attack Jugnauth with
a razor Friday night. But they refused to release any details about
the attack or the assailant.
   Authorities said this Indian Ocan island, which boasts one of
Africa's few multiparty democracies, was calm.
   During a Nov. 6 religious ceremony, a Hindu priest attempted to
shoot Jugnauth with a pistol. The priest was disarmed and the prime
minister, who also is a Hindu like most Mauritians, was not injured.
   Motives for the attack, on which the priest faces charges of
attempted murder, remain unclear.
    Jugnauth came to power in 1982 parliamentary elections and faces
a militant opposition. But he has presided over an economic boom
that has virtually wiped out unemployment in this sugar-producing
island with its growing tourist industry.
   Most of Mauritius' 1 million islanders are Indian-descended
Hindus.
