<SECOND>AM-BRF--Schoolyard Threat,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested In Assault Rifle Threat To School Kids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been arrested for allegedly
telling children at a school that he was going to get an assault
rifle and kill them, Los Angeles County authorities said.
   James Rollin McLane, 27, was arrested Friday and booked for
felony investigation of threatening schoolchildren, sheriff's Deputy
Hal Grant said. No weapons were found in his home.
   McLane, described as an unemployed painter, allegedly made the
threat Wednesday during recess at Grover Cleveland Elementary School.
   ``He confronted several schoolchildren through a chain-link fence
and told them he was going home to get an AR-15 rifle,'' Grant said.
``He said he was going home and would return to kill them.''
   The students told school officials. A deputy recognized the
description and McLane was arrested at his home two blocks from
school, Lt. Michael Kenyon said.
   Cleveland Elementary also is the name of the school in Stockton
where Patrick Purdy, armed with an AK-47 assault rifle, killed five
children and wounded 30 other people in January.
