<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Militants     03-04 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Militants,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Machinists Vow To Continue Strike Even If Company Threatened</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gus Palacias didn't have to walk the Machinists
picket lines that went up Saturday outside Eastern Airlines
headquarters.
   He no longer works there.
   ``But I felt I couldn't turn my back,'' said Palacias, 62, who
retired in December 1987 after 22 years as a Machinists union
aircraft mechanic. ``This is a showdown. I truly believe we have
right on our side. It may just be a showdown to the death.''
   Faced with a foe already accused of breaking one unionized
airline, many in the 8,500-member Eastern Machinists union vow never
to swap their red strike shirts for white surrender flags in the
fight over wages and work conditions.
   Their fervor is not directed at the company, where many union
members have worked since the last strike in 1966, but on its boss,
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo, who acquired Miami-based Eastern
in 1986. Three years earlier, he forced Continental Airlines into
bankruptcy reorganization in 1983 to end a labor confrontation and
abrogate collective bargaining pacts.
   Frank DeMaria, chief steward of the Machinists local in Bayonne,
N.J., said while walking the picket line Saturday: ``The labor of
this country is aware of what a terrorist Frank Lorenzo is. They
consider the dispute not only against Eastern but a dispute for all
labor.''
   ``It's a war,'' said Miami baggage handler Larry Burgess. ``There
are a lot of people here ready to pay any sacrifice to win this
one.''
   Yet many fear the price may be high as the strike could drive
under the 60-year-old company with Lorenzo attempting the same
union-busting strategy used at Continental.
   ``We said we wouldn't worry until the strike came,'' said Pat
Ditzler, whose husband has worked as an Eastern stock clerk for 20
years. ``It's time to worry.''
   Wally Haber, general chairman of the Machinists' Eastern local,
said workers will receive a paycheck Friday then wait two weeks for
$100-a-week strike payments.
   Haber, however, said a decision by pilots and Teamsters to honor
picket lines could force a quick resolution, possibly by White House
intervention.
   ``I predict a 10-day strike with the pilots on our side,'' said
Haber, who fought Eastern management during strikes of six weeks in
1958 and seven weeks in 1966. ``I hope we won't kill the airline,
but Lorenzo was trying to kill us,'' said Haber.
   Eastern management, which claimed the airline has been losing $1
million a day due to high labor costs, was demanding nearly $150
million in Machinists concessions. The union rejected the demand.
   ``The emotions usually die down after the first week,'' said Russ
McGarry, the union's strike coordinator. ``Then we are faced with
the issues of trying to make ends meet at home.''
   The possible loss of paychecks holds different significance for
the union workers, who include mechanics, baggage handlers and other
ground-service workers.
   David Barr, 26, who started as an Eastern mechanic three years
ago, said he'd move on to another job if Eastern fails.
   ``We'll take the company down if we have to,'' said Barr. ``It's
come down to that.''
</TEXT>
