<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Lorenzo     03-04 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Lorenzo,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hard-Nosed Boss's Reputation _ And Company _ On Line</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo's reputation
as one of America's toughest bosses is being tested with the Eastern
Airlines strike, but so is his image as a successful airline builder.
   Since Houston-based Texas Air and its chairman took over Eastern
when it was on the brink of bankruptcy three years ago, the view of
Texas Air as the model for taking advantage of airline deregulation
has been shaken. For all its cost-cutting, Texas Air has been
posting record losses.
   Lorenzo warned Eastern's workers last week that their company
can't survive a strike by Machinists with the pilots and flight
attendants joining in. The unions are gambling that Texas Air can't
survive, either, and that Lorenzo will either yield or sell Eastern
to protect his parent corporation.
   They concede the possibility, though, that he may finish
stripping away Eastern assets and leave a shell, or take the company
into bankruptcy.
   The workers' willingness to fight Lorenzo even at risk to their
future underlines his unpopular management style. Although he bought
Eastern in February 1986 with the slogan ``we aren't union-busters;
we're airline-builders,'' Lorenzo added: ``There ain't no Santa
Claus.''
   The man recently called one of the nation's ``toughest bosses''
and a corporate ``loose cannon'' rolling on deck by ``Fortune''
magazine was born Francisco Antonio Lorenzo 48 years ago to Spanish
immigrants in Queens, N.Y., three miles from La Guardia Airport.
   At one point young Frank drove a truck and belonged to the
Teamsters union.
   Lorenzo, whose schoolboy nickname of ``Frankie Smooth Talk'' was
unearthed by Eastern labor leaders who also sport ``Stop Lorenzo''
buttons, graduated from Columbia and Harvard Business School, worked
at Trans World Airways and Eastern, then in 1971 helped buy
money-losing Texas International, which became Texas Air in 1980.
   With an inner circle of ambitious, hard-driving executives
well-versed in the ways of Wall Street and Washington, Lorenzo has
built Houston-based Texas Air with a takeover of Continental and its
swallowing of such carriers as People Express, New York Air,
Frontier Airlines and other small carriers.
   Continental has been predominantly nonunion since he got labor
contracts abrogated in 1983 bankruptcy reorganization.
   He had mounted unsuccessful efforts to take over National
Airlines and TWA when Eastern's 1986 financial and labor crisis gave
him an opening to buy the major carrier. He gave Eastern's board a
take-it-or-leave-it offer which it accepted after the Machinists
union refused to make major wage concessions.
   Lorenzo at first wouldn't deal directly with Eastern union
leaders, but late last year had dinner with combative Machinists
union head Charles E. Bryan. The meeting led only to more disputes.
   He made direct appeals to pilots and flight attendants in a homey
videotape sent to their homes last week.
   A nonsmoker, ardent jogger and married father of three daughters
and a son, Lorenzo's description of himself as a honest,
hard-working family man doesn't persuade Eastern workers who call
him a corporate terrorist they are determined to fight.
</TEXT>
