<FIRST>r i AM-PLO-US     03-04 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-US,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Official Quoted as Saying US Dialogue Should be Upgraded</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Stands for Jerusalem-dated story on news advisory.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper Saturday quoted a PLO spokesman as
saying informal talks with U.S. officials are ``beating around the
bush'' and that ``serious'' dialogue focusing on an international
peace conference should begin.
   The comments by Yasser Abd-Rabboo, the PLO's information
department chief, were reported by the Al-Anbaa newspaper.
   Abd-Rabboo was quoted as saying the Palestine Liberation
Organization ``notified Washington a week ago that it was time to
resume a serious and in depth dialogue to prepare for an
international conference.''
   ``Dragging on with informal contacts that have been taking place
in Tunis is beating round the bush and will not help bring about a
settlement,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying.
   Abd-Rabboo could not be reached directly for comment, according
to an aide in Tunis, who demanded anonymity. There was no immediate
reaction from the State Department. It did not return telephone
calls from The Associated Press.
   The newspaper article was picked up by Radio Monte Carlo, whose
report was then repeated on Israel's state-run radio and television
Saturday.
   Israeli media reported that Abd-Rabboo said the PLO was not
willing to continue the dialogue with the United State under current
conditions. But such comments did not appear in the Al-Anbaa report
seen in Kuwait.
   Al-Anbaa also quoted Jamal Sourani, a member of the 15-man
Palestine Executive Committee, as saying ``the PLO expects the
dialogue to resume and take its natural course in March or April,
after the crystalization of the American attitude on Palestinian
rights.''
   The United States launched a dialogue with the PLO late last
year, ending a 13-year boycott of such talks after PLO chairman
Yasser Arafat renounced terrorism and recognized the state of Israel.
   Israel, which considers the PLO a terrorist organization,
repeatedly has urged Washington to end the talks, citing what it
calls continuing PLO attacks.
   The State Department warned Friday that recent clashes between
Palestinian guerrillas and Israeli troops in south Lebanon could
have a negative impact on the dialogue. Israel said the Palestinians
were trying to infiltrate Israel.
   Palestinian leaders say military operations against Israel were
not included in Arafat's commitment renouncing terrorism.
   Arafat said Friday that Palestinian guerrillas will continue to
strike back during Israeli raids on their bases in south Lebanon.
Arafat's closest aide, Salah Kahlaf, was quoted as saying Saturday
that Washington is ``still hesitant'' about its dialogue with the
PLO and that was the reason for its warning.
   Radio Monte Carlo, based in Paris, also quoted him as saying,
``Military operations are not acts of terrorism.''
   ``Our definition of terrorism is very clear. Any operation abroad
(outside Israel) in which civilians, including Israelis, are killed,
is terrorism,'' said Khalaf, co-founder of Arafat's Fatah faction.
   The radio did not say where he was interviewed.
</TEXT>
