<FIRST>r a AM-SecretReport     03-04 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Secret Report,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Worker Finds Secret Government Weapons Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An employee at a safe company uncovered a
40-page secret weapons report from the U.S. Department of Energy
after he drilled open a discarded safe.
   John Wilson of the Johnson Safe Co. said he found the government
report lodged between two shelves of a safe he drilled open Friday.
   The safe was in a lot of five safes bought from a Cincinnati
surplus outlet, company owner Chuck Johnson said.
   The cover of the document is dated May 24, 1988, and says
``Defense Program _ Weapons Activities.'' The words ``Working
Papers,'' ``Restricted Data'' and ``Secret'' also were stamped on
it. One handwritten word, ``Destroy,'' slants through the title.
   The report contains references to cruise missiles and bombers and
charts of weapon stockpiles.
   ``You'd have to be an expert in that field to know what it's all
about,'' said Eva Johnson, Chuck Johnson's wife. ``The average
layman wouldn't understand anything in it. It's Greek to them.''
   Johnson said he will take the report to the FBI on Monday.
   Al Taylor, an FBI agent in Cincinnati, declined to comment
Saturday on the discovery, but said FBI officials in Columbus would
be notified.
</TEXT>
