<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Bryan     03-04 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bryan,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Leader In Toughest Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Machinists union faced down
Eastern chairman Frank Borman and then the airline's board, and his
refusal to give in to new owner Frank Lorenzo spurred Saturday's
strike at Eastern.
   Charles E. Bryan, 55, is depicted by Eastern management as a
hate-filled, near-maniacal union boss. In a recently published,
red-colored booklet called ``Charlie Says...'', the company warns
that he will destroy the airline.
   Borman, the former Eastern chairman and Apollo 8 astronaut who
admits he was driven to tears by Bryan, recently compared him to
Peoples Temple cult leader Jim Jones, who led a mass suicide in 1978.
   But Bryan's union members trust him and follow him implicitly.
Many other Eastern employees have come to admire his persistent,
often-innovative strategies, which Bryan credits to an extensive
self-education that included study of the Bible, Zen, yoga, the
ancient Chinese handbook ``The Art of War,'' and the philosophies of
Gandhi and Martin Luther King Jr.
   Bryan says he has learned from studying their philosophies that
resistance based on inner good and following the right way will
triumph. His critics say Bryan's philosophy is based on egotism and
stubbornness _ or worse.
   Bryan has charged repeatedly that the Lorenzo management wants
only to bust the unions and strip away Eastern's assets before
abandoning the carcass.
   Joseph Guerrieri Jr., a veteran Washington labor lawyer who
represents the Machinists, says Bryan never ceases to impress him
with his drive and creativity.
   The divorced father of three grown children appears to have
unlimited stamina and is equally comfortable in corporate
boardrooms, courtrooms, running news conferences or leading fiery
union rallies.
   Borman says Bryan has ``a certifiably insane dream'' of running
Eastern himself.
   ``Deregulation's full impact on Eastern's fortunes and Charlie
Bryan's rise to power as a union leader arrived on the scene
virtually in tandem, twin omens of our troubled future,'' Borman
wrote in his autobiography, ``Countdown.''
   Bryan, an Eastern mechanic since 1956 and elected to head its
largest union in 1980, has been trying to spur employee control of
the company. He says workers would be more productive and provide
better service if they had more say in the company, which he says
has been pushed into financial desperation by years of poor
management.
   Bryan threatened a strike in 1983 and Borman gave in with a 32
percent raise for the Machinists. Borman says Eastern then didn't
have enough cash to withstand a strike, and that the pay demands
were irresponsible because Bryan knew Eastern couldn't afford them.
   In 1986, Eastern's board demanded 20 percent wage concessions
from its unions, saying the company would go into bankruptcy without
them. The pilots and flight attendants agreed; Bryan said no
concessions unless Borman was fired.
   The board said it couldn't allow such a demand and voted to sell
to Texas Air. Bryan sent Lorenzo a conciliatory telegram. He got no
answer and instead was stripped of his seat on the board and of
other privileges.
   That began a struggle Bryan describes as between workers whose
home has been invaded by a hostile force, even a battle between good
and evil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
