<DOCNO> AP890304-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-StrikeGlance     03-04 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Strike Glance,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Strike's Effects In Airline's Major Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a city-by-city wrapup of the effects of the Eastern
Airlines strike at key airports and transit systems.
   In general, almost all Eastern flights were canceled Saturday,
despite the airlines' contingency plan to run a skeleton schedule;
effects on other airlines and mass transit were negligible.
   MIAMI: Pickets at airport, nearby Eastern corporate headquarters
and reservations system center of Texas Air Corp., Eastern's parent.
No violence reported. As of midafternoon, seven flights had left the
airport; normal daily schedule calls for 109 departures. No reported
problems at other airlines or local transit services.
   ORLANDO, Fla.: Some 140 pickets were working in shifts at about
half-a-dozen locations. No flights departed; on a normal day 31
flights scheduled. No reports of violence or problems at other
airlines.
   ATLANTA: Machinists and uniformed pilots picketed outside
terminal and in Eastern concourses. Eastern had scheduled 278
departures for Saturday; only a few left. Nails were scattered in an
Eastern parking lot but no violence or traffic delays reported.
   BALTIMORE-Baltimore-Washington International: Four Machinists
pickets _ the maximum allowed by the airport. No violence or work
slowdowns at other airlines reported. All 10 departures canceled.
   NEWARK, N.J.: About 80 strikers on picket lines. Machinists
joined by pilots and flight attendants. All flights canceled. Extra
police assigned but no problems reported. NJ Transit officials ask a
federal judge to issue injunction to head off threatened secondary
strike Monday.
   NEW YORK-La Guardia: More than 120 Eastern machinists and other
unions' pilots and flight attendants walk picket lines. All but one
flight canceled. No violence or arrests. Other airport operations
reported normal.
   NEW YORK-Kennedy: Eastern machinists and supporters from other
unions totaled about 110. Eastern suspended all operations for at
least the weekend. No violence or arrests reported. Other airport
operations reported normal.
   New York commuter rail service reported normal; transit officials
Saturday sought injunction against threatened Monday secondary
strike.
   WASHINGTON-National: Virtually no Eastern pilots crossed picket
lines. Fifty-six flights canceled, all Sunday flights
canceled.Amtrak said it was adding four Metroliner trains on
Washington-New York route Saturday.
   BOSTON: About 50 picketers at the Eastern terminal at any one
time Saturday. Federal judge issued temporary restraining order
Saturday against airport operator allowing limited picketing at TWA
and United. No violence reported. Of 48 Eastern flights scheduled,
two had left by midafternoon. Massachusetts Bay Transportation
Authority said it was preparing for expected Monday sympathy walkout
on commuter railways.
   PHILADELPHIA: About 50 Eastern machinists, pilots and attendants
picketed airport. No violence reported; no sympathy walkouts in
other airlines reported. Of 40 flights ordinarily scheduled, only
one departed. The Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority
obtained a temporary restraining order preventing unionized
railworkers from a sympathy strike.
   CHICAGO-O'Hare: About 45 people carrying picket signs protested
outside airport. No violence reported. All 16 flights canceled.
   LOS ANGELES: All 11 flights canceled. Peaceful picketing
reported. Two-hundred strikers and supporters rally.
   KANSAS CITY, Mo.: Two dozen Eastern machinists picketed outside
airline gates and cargo building. All flights canceled; airport
handles six Eastern flights on a typical day. No violence reported.
   RALEIGH, N.C. : About 20 strikers picketed a terminal; all nine
daily flights canceled.
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The two Eastern flights canceled. Machinists,
working in shifts of four or five, picketed in an airport lobby. In
Greer, S.C., all 11 Eastern flights scheduled over the weekend out
of Greenville-Spartanburg Airport were canceled.
   DETROIT: All nine daily flights canceled.
   RICHMOND, Va.: All five flights canceled. Other airlines said
flights were filling up. Because of airport security rules, only
four pickets were allowed at the airport _ two inside and two
outside.
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Seven local strikers picketed outside Eastern's
ticket counter. Eastern's five daily departures canceled.
   HOUSTON _ About 16 people manned picket line at Hobby Airport,
including Eastern pilots and flight attendants. Four daily flights
canceled.
   PROVIDENCE, R.I.: Four pickets stand peacefully on sidewalk
outside T.F. Green State Airport. All Eastern flights canceled.
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico: About 30 machinists picketed peacefully in
front of Eastern terminal at Munoz Marin International Airport. Most
of 24 daily Eastern flights canceled.
