<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     03-04 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Kosovo Party Boss Leader Of Separatist Group, Newspaper Alleges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recently ousted Communist Party
chief of the restive Kosovo province was a leader of an outlawed
group seeking secession of the region from Yugoslavia, a state-run
newspaper alleged Saturday.
   The daily Vecernje Novosti claimed Azem Vlasi, who headed
Kosovo's ruling Politburo from 1986-88, was a ``staff officer of a
provincial counter-revolutionary group'' working to unite Kosovo
with neighboring Albania.
   Vlasi was among about 20 leading ethnic Albanian party officials
or company directors in Kosovo who have been arrested since Thursday
in a crackdown on ethnic Albanian dissent there.
   Most allegedly belonged to the illegal group that reportedly
planned to destabilize the province by strikes and protests and then
carry out an armed uprising that would secede the predominantly
ethnic Albanian region from Yugoslavia.
   Vecernje Novosti reported what it said were initial results of
the police investigation underway after the massive arrests and
detentions of prominent Kosovo public figures.
   The arrests came after widespread protests by ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo against planned constitutional changes they fear will limit
autonomy of the region which administratively belongs to the
republic of Serbia.
   Last Monday, emergency measures were introduced in Kosovo in an
attempt to prevent possible clashes between the ethnic Albanian
majority and the Slav minority there.
   Serbia's ambitious Communist Party boss, Slobodan Milosevic,
vowed on Tuesday at a counter-demonstration by over 500,000 Serbs in
Belgrade that the ``organizers'' of the ethnic Albanian protests
would be ``punished and arrested.''
   Vlasi, 41, was the chief opponent of Milosevic's centralist
policies and is one of the most popular leaders among about 2
million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
   For his consistent opposition to Serbia's policies toward Kosovo
he was voted out of the country's 165-member policy-setting Central
Committee in February.
   Vecernje Novosti said that Vlasi was arrested while planning to
travel to West Germany along with his wife. His two brothers are
reportedly living there.
   Belgrade newspapers said Saturday that about 50 prominent public
figures, including several provincial party officials, may face
criminal prosecution in connection with their alleged role in recent
ethnic Albanian unrest.
   Meanwhile, the official Serbian press is increasingly implying
that Yugoslavia's liberal Slovenian republic was allegedly
instigating the ethnic Albanian unrest in Kosovo.
   It has alleged that Vlasi secretly visited Slovenia last month
and that he was planning to become the director a Slovenian bank in
the provincial capital of Pristina.
   Slovenia, which itself fears alleged Serbian hegemony, has
supported ethnic Albanian demands for guarantees that the autonomy
of their province will not be curtailed by changes of the
constitution.
</TEXT>
