<SECOND>AM-Most Wanted, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Arrest Fugitive Charged with Molesting Child</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS next-to-last graf, ``Jones was ...,'' to CORRECT charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUTTE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list for
fleeing child molestation charges was arrested while living under an
alias at a campground, the FBI said Saturday.
   Roger Lee Jones, 43, of Sarasota, Fla., was arrested at a KOA
campgroundon burglary charges stemming from a February service
station robbery in Great Falls, 150 miles north of Butte, FBI agent
Toby Harding said.
   Jones, who used the alias Mike Andrews, admitted his true
identity in custody, Harding said.
   He was held without bond in the Great Falls jail on charges of
burglary and felony theft, and was scheduled to appear before a
Cascade County justice of the peace Monday, Great Falls police Sgt.
Russell Sinnott said.
   Harding said authorities in Great Falls and Florida will decide
whether Jones will face charges in Montana or be transported back to
Florida.
   Jones was arrested in Florida in August 1986 and charged with
three counts of sexual battery, that state's rape statute; three
counts of lewd and lascivious conduct and one count of sexual
performance by a child, Harding said. Jones fled the area after
posting bond.
   Jones was charged under federal statutes in March 1987 with
unlawful flight to avoid prosecution, and placed on the most-wanted
list last May.
