<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 1836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-CommunistDropouts     03-04 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Communist Dropouts,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disillusioned Communists Quitting Party, Pravda Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Communist Party members are resigning because
they don't want to be associated with former leaders Josef Stalin
and Leonid Brezhnev, Pravda said Saturday in an article urging
Communists to face up to their painful past.
   For decades, the Soviet government hid sordid chapters of its
history and even glorified Stalin during his lifetime. But under
President Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, the
national press has been full of reports on repression and death
under Stalin and corruption under Brezhnev.
   Many older communists have reacted with shock and dismay at the
denigration of their heroes.
   Pravda, the official Communist Party newspaper, specifically
cited electrician Sergei K. Chapayev and M. Zapodoinikov, a teacher,
both from the Gorno-Altai region in western Siberia, as members who
had dropped out because they were disillusioned.
   It said others have done the same but gave no figures.
   ``All my life appears to be worthless,'' Chapayev, who was a
party member for 19 years before quitting recently, was quoted as
saying.
   ``All my life I believed, and now all is gone to ashes, and not a
blessed thing remains. Stalin, Molotov, Voroshilov .... we were
singing songs about them. We believed in them more than we believed
in ourselves,'' he said.
   Vyacheslav M. Molotov, foreign minister during the prewar pact
with Nazi Germany, and Kliment E. Voroshilov were two of Stalin's
closest aides during the years when the Stalinist secret police
killed millions of Soviet citizens.
   Pravda quoted Zapodoinikov as saying, ``I cannot remain a member
of the party which had Brezhnev, Kunayev, Nasriddinova and other
scum in its ranks.''
   Dinmukhamed Kunayev and Vadgar Nasriddinova are former regional
party officials named in corruption scandals.
   Pravda correspondent E. Solomenko said the two disaffected party
members from Gorno-Altai were not isolated cases but part of a
larger problem dating back years.
   He said he remembered Leningrad party members quitting during
Brezhnev's time, saying: ``It's because we cannot live anymore in
lies and hypocrisy.''
   The newspaper said that although some might argue that the
shameful portions of the party's history should be kept quiet, true
party members should be able to stand up and face the truth.
   Admitting the truth, Pravda concluded, is painful but necessary.
   ``This is a pain similar to that which occurs when light strikes
the eyes of a man who has long been in darkness and finally emerges
into the sun, or when a doctor restores sight to a blind man, and
takes from his eyes the black blindfold. Thus goes the revelation,''
the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
