<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     03-04 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls on Evans, Sawyer to Unite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson began a three-day fast Saturday to
urge Mayor Eugene Sawyer and mayoral candidate Timothy Evans to
unite and preserve the coalition formed by former Mayor Harold
Washington.
   ``Harold Washington died and our ship wrecked,'' Jackson told a
rally at the headquarters of Operation PUSH, the civil rights group
he founded.
   ``Rather than pick up the pieces, we chose to bomb the ship,''
Jackson said. ``Now we must build a new ship in five weeks.''
   Evans, a black Democratic alderman running as an independent,
refused to endorse Sawyer in last Tuesday's Democratic mayoral
primary, which was won by Cook County State's Attorney Richard M.
Daley.
   Jackson endorsed Sawyer, who is also black, in the primary and
now supports Evans.
   Sawyer has so far declined to endorse Evans for the general
election April 4.
   ``Division is our problem; unity and coalition are our
solution,'' Jackson said. ``An Evans-Sawyer summit is essential.''
   Washington, the city's first black mayor, died in November 1987.
The election this spring is to fill the remaining two years of his
second term.
   After Washington's death, Sawyer, a former alderman, was selected
acting mayor by the City Council. Daley, who is white, is the son of
the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, who ruled Chicago for 21 years.
   Former Alderman Edward Vrdolyak, who was Washington's archrival
while a Democrat, won the Republican primary Tuesday. Vrdolyak is
white.
   ``There are those who say the only issue in the campaign is
race,'' Jackson said. ``That's not true, but it's a major issue. The
issue is not black and white; it's backward and forward.''
   Sawyer was out of the country and could not be reached for
comment, but spokesman Monroe Anderson said he doubted Jackson's
appeal would persuade Sawyer to endorse Evans.
   ``The mayor has indicated that he's going to remain neutral,''
Anderson said. ``He just wants to remain above the fray.''
   Evans spokesman Rene Camargo said the alderman was campaigning
and could not be reached for comment.
   Jackson defended his support of Evans over Daley, the Democratic
nominee, saying that Daley did not support Washington in the 1987
election campaign, and that Daley did not support Jackson's own bid
for the presidency.
   ``I support fairness. I support coalition,'' Jackson said. ``But
I am not a masochist. I support fairness and reciprocity in return.''
   Daley spokeswoman Avis LaVelle said Daley was out of town and
could not be reached for comment, but said Daley had asked Sawyer to
support the Democratic nominee.
   ``We see that Reverend Jackson's influence was not very
persuasive when he asked Tim Evans to support Eugene Sawyer,'' Ms.
LaVelle said. ``It remains to be seen what effect his appeal will
have on Mayor Sawyer.''
</TEXT>
