<SECOND>AM-Laos-MIAS,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laos Postpones MIA Excavation With the United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laos on Saturday postponed a scheduled
joint excavation with the United States to search for the remains of
missing American soldiers, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok said.
   A 14-member team of U.S. experts was to fly to Laos aboard two
C-130 transport planes Sunday morning for the dig, but the Laotians
did not give the planes clearance to enter, spokesman Ross Petzing
said.
   Petzing refused to comment when asked why Laos put the project on
hold.
   However, the Laotians may have been irritated when the United
States earlier this week criticized them for allegedly failing to
cooperate in the war against narcotics.
   An annual report that Secretary of State James Baker sent to
Congress lists a handful of countries that it declares ineligible
for U.S. aid because of their support for drug trafficking.
   In the report, which was released Wednesday, President Bush
recommended that Burma and Laos be added to that list.
   The report said U.S. officials believe opium production is
expanding in Laos and that heroin is being refined there for export
through Thailand, Vietnam and China.
   U.S. officials have said there is evidence that Laotian officials
are involved in the processing and smuggling of drugs. When that
charge surfaced in last year's narcotics report to Congress, the
Laotian government issued a stern denial.
   The United States is trying to account for 547 Americans listed
as missing in action in Laos during the Vietnam war. Many were
airmen who flew reconnaissance and bombing missions.
   Laos had conducted four joint excavations with the United States.
The first one was in Feb. 1985.
   The Pentagon said the latest excavation was to have been
conducted in an area in southern Savannakhet province which a
U.S.-Laotian team had surveyed last December. However, the United
States has no record of a U.S. plane crashing there.
   Petzing said the U.S. team had planned to work 8-10 days at the
site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890304-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Soviet     03-04 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Soviet,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Slams Breshnev; Gorbachev Approves Of Hungary's Multiparty
System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official on Saturday said
Hungary was reduced to ``a kind of servility'' to the Soviet Union
during the regime of Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev.
   The comments by Central Committee secretary Matyas Szueroes came
a day after Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was reported as
approving of Budapest's plans to introduce a multi-party system.
   Szueroes, in an interview in the Magyar Nemzet daily, first
praised the Soviet Union's 1945 ``liberation'' of Hungary to remove
``one of the most backward and poorest feudal-capitalist regimes.''
   However, he was reported as saying after 1948 ``relations no
longer developed in the spirit of equal rights and mutual benefits.
   ``The Brezhnev doctrine (of limited sovereignty of Moscow's
allies) caused a further deformation, accompanied by great power
aspects on the one side, and a kind of servility on the other, as
well as insistence on certain dogmas until the mid-1980s,'' Szueroes
was quoted as saying.
   Hungary's ``servility'' was not explained. But under the
leadership of former Premier Janos Kadar, Hungary heeded a Soviet
call to join in the invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968 to crush the
short-lived ``Prague Spring'' reforms spearheaded by then party
leader Alexander Dubcek.
   Romania was the only Warsaw Pact country that refused to take
part in the military intervention.
   Szueroes also said, ``The antipathy and reservations with which
the Soviet Union and, in general, the socialist world, followed the
reform process in Hungary was a fundamental cause of the halt to the
reform.''
   One victim of Kadar's halt to the economic reform was Reszoe
Nyers, its chief architect, who was ousted from the Politburo in
1973. As Kadar was removed in May last year, Nyers joined the
Politburo again and now serves also in the government.
   Szueroes's comments were an indication of gradually increasing
openness in exposing the political shortcomings and economic
failures during Kadar's 32-year tenure.
   Word that Gorbachev does not oppose Hungarian moves toward
introducing a multi-party system came from Premier Miklos Nemeth as
he was traveling back to Budapest from a visit to the Soviet Union.
   ``The general secretary (of the Soviet Communist Party) welcomed
the idea of pluralism (in Hungary), since he considers the (process
of) representation, institutionalization and confrontation of
opinions and interests ... to be at the core of democracy,'' Nemeth
was quoted as saying by the state news agency MTI late Friday.
   According to Nemeth, Gorbachev said the Soviety Union seeks
pluralism within a one-party system, yet he would not reprimand the
Hungarian leadership for its decision to introduce a multi-party
system.
   But Gorbachev reportedly stressed that ``a multi-party system
should not be seen as a panacea.''
   In the interview with Magyar Nemzet, Szueroes made clear that
Hungary's political links with the Soviet bloc alliance system must
not prejudice its economic interests.
   The Hungarian economy has serious interests in its cooperation
with the Soviet Union, Szueroes was quoted as saying.
   ``This, however, must be based on economic advantages, and
affiliation with the same (Warsaw Pact) alliance system must be
clearly separated from asserting the economic interests.''
   Before he went to Moscow, Nemeth bluntly stated that COMECON, the
Soviet-dominated Eastern trading alliance, brings more disadvantages
than advantages for member countries.
   Nemeth quoted Gorbachev, too, as saying that COMECON should
undergo ``a drastic transformation.''
</TEXT>
