<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TankerAground 2ndLd-Writethru a0586 03-04 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Aground, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0586,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Damage To Tanker Assessed; Cleanup Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with estimate of spill revised
downward to 33,000 sted 117,000; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Some of ...''
^By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews worked Saturday to remove thick oil that
had washed in along a 2-mile stretch of shoreline, while the Coast
Guard checked damage to a tanker that spilled 33,000 gallons of oil
when it ran aground, authorities said.
   Coast Guard officials said it appeared no more oil would come
ashore, and made a major revision in the estimate of the amount of
oil spilled, which originally had been put at 117,000 gallons.
   The 800-foot tanker Exxon Houston floated free of a reef Friday
evening, about 24 hours after a storm drove it aground off a
little-used stretch of coast 15 miles west of Honolulu and its famed
Waikiki Beach.
   Coast Guard spokesman David Goff said that of 92,000 gallons of
bunker fuel oil feared lost from the tanker's ruptured fuel tank,
84,000 were found in the tank Saturday, meaning 8,000 gallons were
lost.
   About 25,000 gallons of crude oil spilled into the ocean Thursday
when the ship tore away from its mooring and floating hoses
unloading the oil pulled free.
   Some of the spilled oil washed to sea during the night, said
Randal O'Grydziak, with the Coast Guard's Marine Safety Office in
Honolulu.
   ``For the most part, it looks pretty good,'' O'Grydziak said.
``Mother Nature overnight has through some tide changes done away
with a lot of the (petroleum) product.''
   He said cleanup crews worked to remove oil-soaked vegetation,
soak up oil in water pools in the coral reef and rake the affected
beaches.
   The state Department of Health had closed beaches along the
soiled shoreline, O'Grydziak said.
   Libert K. Landgraf, deputy director of the state Department of
Land and Natural Resources, said there was no immediate evidence of
injury or death to marine life or birds.
   Coast Guard spokesman Keith Spangler flew over the tanker and
shoreline Saturday morning and said no more oil was visible around
the ship or off the coast.
   ``I really think most of it's ashore,'' Spangler said.
   Coast Guard Lt. Brad Nelson said officials at the scene believed
the pollution would be limited to the shoreline already affected.
   ``They're saying, `If you have to have an oil disaster, this is
the one to have,''' Nelson said.
   The Coast Guard's Pacific Area Biological-Chemical Strike Team
arrived from San Francisco late Friday and was standing by with a
floating boom that skims oil off the ocean surface, Nelson said.
   He said the team had not decided whether to use the 612-foot
boom, which is towed between two ships.
   The Clean Islands Council, a Hawaii oil spill cleanup
cooperative, was contracted to perform the cleanup by Exxon Co. USA,
the Houston-based domestic oil and gas division of Exxon Corp. Exxon
Co. USA, will pay for the costs of the cleanup, according to Exxon
attorney Leonard Alcantara.
   Officials had planned to wait until high tide early Saturday to
attempt to remove the tanker from the reef.
   But it floated free on its own late Friday after workers pumped
off more than 9,400 tons of ballast water and some of the remaining
3.8 million gallons of crude oil, lightening the ship to prevent
more crude oil or ship's fuel from spilling, said Scott Hartvigsen,
another Coast Guard spokesman.
   The tanker was moved to deep water five miles offshore and a Navy
ship and three tugboats had lines attached to the vessel, Nelson
said. A Coast Guard cutter and Navy salvage ship also were with the
ship.
   There was no problem keeping the tanker afloat, Nelson said.
   The ship ran aground late Thursday after high wind and rough seas
tore it from its offshore mooring.
   The Exxon Houston had unloaded 400,000 barrels of Alaska crude
oil at the mooring a mile off the Hawaiian Independent Refinery at
the time, said Capt. Gordon Piche, commander of the Coast Guard's
Marine Safey Office.
</TEXT>
