<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-04 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Seeks U.N. Flood Prevention Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bangladesh on Saturday asked U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to help mobilize
international support for solving the country's perennial flood
problems, an official said.
   Perez de Cuellar, who has visited India and will fly to Nepal on
Monday as part of a tour of the region, met Foreign Minister Anisul
Islam Mahmoud and responded favorably, according to a source who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The source, who is close to the talks, gave no further details.
   More than 1,400 people were killed and 25 million were left
homeless last summer when floods submerged three-fourths of this
country of 110 million people.
   Bangladesh has been seeking a regional approach, involving India
and Nepal, for solving the flood problems. India has repeatedly
rejected the idea, saying Bangladesh was trying to
``internationalize'' a bilateral matter between the two neighbors.
   Bangladesh's major rivers originate in India and Nepal. During
the monsoon season, the rivers are swollen by rains and cascade down
from the Himalayan mountains and foothills.
   Although parts of India also are prone to floods, the surging
rivers' greatest fury usually is unleashed on the low-lying nation
of Bangladesh.
   U.N. And Bangladeshi environmental and development officials have
said deforestation in India and Nepal contributes to the problem,
because of a decline in soil retention of water.
   The independent Sangbad newspaper and other Dhaka dailies
recently reported Bangladesh has drawn up a 6 billion dollar flood
control plan. The government has neither confirmed nor denied the
report.
   A joint U.N.-Bangladesh task force has said the country needs at
least 1.1 billion dollars for reconstruction and flood relief after
last year's flood.
   With a per capital annual income of about $160, Bangladesh is one
of the world's poorest nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
