<FIRST>r a AM-SeaLionReturns     03-04 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Lion Returns,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tagged Sea Lion Returns To Feed On Ship-Locks Fish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sea lion relocated to the Pacific Ocean in a
campaign to stop the mammals from feasting on local fish returned to
its hunting grounds here after traveling nearly 300 miles, a
wildlife official said Saturday.
   The California sea lion spotted near the Ballard ship locks
Friday afternoon was the first relocated animal to return.
   ``He obviously likes it here,'' said Bob Byrne of the state
Department of Wildlife. ``He knows a good life when he finds one.''
   The sea lions wait by the locks and pick off steelhead, a
seagoing trout, and salmon that are en route to their spawning
grounds.
   Officials have trapped 18 sea lions so far using a floating cage.
Two died after being sedated for tagging and five more were released
at the locks because of cold weather.
   To return, the sea lion had to swim about 150 miles up the coast,
turn right, swim another 100 miles through the Strait of Juan de
Fuca, turn right again and paddle the remaining 35 miles to the
locks.
   Trapping will probably resume Monday, and officials are confident
they can catch the remaining 13 or so animals, including the one who
returned, for relocation to the Pacific, Byrne said.
</TEXT>
