<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     03-04 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon Concerned At Reports Israel Will Expand Security Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Moslem and Christian cabinets in
Lebanon's dual government on Saturday issued statements voicing
concern over a reported plan by Israel to expand its self-declared
security zone in southern Lebanon.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem cabinet,
told Lebanon's envoy to the United Nations, Rashid Fakhoury, to
``draw the world's attention to Israel's intentions,'' an official
statement said.
   The rival Christian cabinet of Gen. Michel Aoun, in a statement
published by the independent daily An-Nahar, expressed ``deep
concern over the statements made by some Israeli military commanders
which clearly revealed Israel's intention to widen the area of what
it calls the security zone.''
   Maj. Gen. Youssi Peled, Israel's northern front commander,, was
quoted Thursday as saying he was considering expanding the security
zone.
   Voice of the South radio, the mouthpiece of the Israeli-allied
South Lebanon Army militia that operates in the zone, said Peled
wanted to include five Druse villages in the strip.
   The broadcast said the move was requested by unnamed leaders of
the Mimes, Khalwat, Ein Senta, Kfir and Ein Ata villages located in
the central Bekaa valley, a few miles north of the security zone.
   The Moslem-run Voice of the Nation radio, based in west Beirut,
broadcast statements issued in the five villages that denied making
such a request or having contacts with the Israelis in the security
zone.
   ``Peled's statement reflects his intention to widen the security
zone,'' the broadcast said.
   Israel kept control of a 6-to-10-mile deep zone when it withdrew
the bulk of its occupation army from south Lebanon in summer 1985.
   The strip extending from the Mediterranean coast in the west to
the slopes of Mount Hermon in the east serves as a buffer against
cross-border guerrilla attacks on northern Israeli settlements.
   Lebanon has had rival Moslem and Christian governments since last
September, when outgoing President Amin Gemayel appointed Aoun to
head an interim military cabinet after Parliament failed to elect a
new president.
   Moslems refused to accept Aoun's appointment and pledged loyalty
to Hoss, who served as prime minister in the Gemayel administration.
</TEXT>
