<DOCNO> AP890304-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-PeaceTalks     03-04 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Peace Talks,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Guerrillas, Government Hold Second Day of Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas and government officials from
Colombia on Saturday resumed peace talks interrupted by the shooting
death of a leftist leader at Bogota's airport.
   The talks were the third between the two sides this year in
search of a way to end a quarter-century of political violence in
Colombia.
   Antonio Navarro Wolf, leader of the delegation from the rebels'
April 19 Movement, told reporters before entering the talks that
rebels had ``a concrete proposal'' to present to the government.
   He did not say what the proposal contained but described it as
``what we think has to be done on an emergency basis to strengthen
and broaden this process to respond to death with life, to darkness
with hope and to war with peace.''
   Before Friday's session Wolf said the talks were intended to set
the stage for a peace agreement in Colombia.
   Rafael Pardo Ruedo, the government's representative, said the
Bogota government continued to support the talks as a move toward
peace.
   ``It is a process that can be difficult but is a light of hope
for Colombia at this time,'' he said.
   ``The road that must be followed is the road to democracy. The
majority of Colombians believe that democracy is the solution,'' he
said.
   Before entering the session at a luxury hotel, representatives of
both sides condemned the killing Friday of Jose Antequera, an
executive board member of the Marxist-oriented Patriotic Union, and
another man and the wounding of eight others at Bogota's El Dorado
Airport.
   Antequera, whose party was formed by the guerrillas, was the
apparent target of the attack, authorities in Bogota said. He had
received death threats from right-wing paramilitary organizations in
Colombia.
   He and other political leaders, accompanied by bodyguards, had
arrived at the airport to fly to Cucuta, near the Venezuelan border
and Barranquilla, on the Atlantic coast.
   An official from the Attorney General's office also was killed
and bodyguards killed one of the attackers, police said. Three other
attackers were captured.
   More than 75,000 Colombians have died in political violence in
Colombia in the past 25 years. More than 1,000 have been killed in
the last three years.
   The April 19 Movement is the largest of the six insurgent groups
and has about 10,000 members.
   The first day of talks ended early Friday when delegates learned
of the shooting.
   The talks were a continuation of meetings between the guerrillas
and government Jan. 10 and Feb. 8 in Colombia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
