<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     03-04 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Seeks Roh's Resignation In Referendum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders agreed Saturday to
seek the resignation of President Roh Tae-woo in a referendum on his
performance the government promised to hold in April.
   Leaders of South Korea's three rival opposition parties, Kim
Dae-jung, Kim Young-sam and Kim Jong-pil, issued a joint declaration
after narrowing differences on key political issues.
   The three agreed on a common approach to the referendum Roh had
promised in December 1987, just before he won presidential elections.
   The declaration issued Saturday urged Roh to hold a promised
referendum after ``bringing about sizable results'' in redressing
corruption and power abuses left over from his predecessor, Chun
Doo-hwan.
   ``Otherwise, we will launch a no-confidence campaign to push for
Roh's resignation,'' it said.
   The three Kims accused Roh of insincerity in introducing reforms.
   The opposition agreement came as the government began preparing
for the referendum, aimed at seeking an early settlement of thorny
political issues without damaging its credibility.
   Senior government leaders agreed Saturday to hold the referendum
in early April, but they suggested that in the referendum, voters
should assess the administration's handling of specific issues
rather than its overall performance.
   The government party lacks broad public support, but party
leaders have said Roh is confident of victory in a referendum.
   Despite broad reforms Roh has introduced since taking office in
February, opponents have staged protests demanding his ouster.
   Recent surveys show many South Koreans believe the government
failed to take firm action to deal with past government abuses.
Dissidents and radical students identify Roh with Chun's
authoritarian government.
   Roh has asked the nation to pardon Chun since the former
president went into rural exile last November after making an open
apology for misdeeds during his seven-year administration.
   In Saturday's meeting, government leaders reaffirmed their
rejection of an opposition demand that Chun be made to testify
before the opposition-controlled National Assembly on human rights
violations and other abuses.
</TEXT>
