<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2159EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Thayer     03-04 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Thayer,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Herald Tribune President Dies Of Pneumonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter N. Thayer III, a lawyer, political adviser
and corporate executive who guided the New York Herald Tribune in
its declining years, died Saturday of pneumonia. He was 78.
   Thayer, who was president of the International Herald Tribune and
a partner in the Whitcom Investment Co., was being treated at New
York Hospital when he died, according to Bernard Kiernan, a
spokesman for the family.
   Thayer was a close associate of the late financier John Hay
Whitney, on whose behalf Thayer arranged for the purchase of the
financially troubled New York Herald Tribune in 1958.
   Although his first job was as a newspaper reporter and he was
involved in the news industry for much of his life, Thayer did not
fashion himself a journalist. ``I do not have printer's ink in my
blood,'' he once said.
   Kiernan said Thayer advised numerous politicians, including
President Dwight D. Eisenhower, New York Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller
and New York Mayor John V. Lindsay.
   He had a reputation as a shrewd and well-paid lawyer who drove a
hard bargain.
   In his book, ``The Paper: The Life and Death of the New York
Herald Tribune,'' Richard Kluger wrote: ``Smart, clear-thinking,
hardheaded, as personable as any man when he chose to be, Thayer
also came to be perceived as cold, guarded, very private and almost
ruthlessly dismissive of those he found unworthy or unuseful.''
   Thayer was born in Dannemora, N.Y. and, after graduating from
high school at age 16, worked as a news reporter for $12 a week on
the Ellenville, N.Y. Press.
   After earning a law degree at Yale University, he became an
assistant U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of New York in
1937. After World War II, he helped found the New York law firm of
Thayer & Gilbert; in 1956, he joined J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. as managing
partner.
   After Whitney purchased the New York Herald Tribune in 1958,
Thayer became its president and remained in that position until a
strike in 1966 forced the newspaper to cease publication.
   In 1967, Thayer became president of the board of directors of the
International Herald Tribune, which was formed when the Paris Herald
Tribune joined forces with The New York Times and The Washington
Post.
   Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, publisher of the Times, said Thayer was
responsible for much of the Tribune's success in dealing with its
partners.
   ``Much of this was due to Walter Thayer's willingness to
listen,'' Sulzberger said in a statement. ``Further, he was blessed
by a good nose for news and high standards of journalistic
excellence.''
   Thayer is survived by his wife, the former Jeanne Cooley Greeley;
a son, Thomas of Los Angeles; and three daughters, Ann Thayer of New
York City, Susan Noble of Greenport, N.Y. and Gail Richter of
Lexington, Okla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
