<DOCNO> AP890304-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 2213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlagArt     03-04 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Teacher Charged With Desecrating Flag in Banner Brouhaha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A schoolteacher in town for a seminar became
entangled in a controversy over the use of an American flag in an
art exhibit Saturday when she was arrested for walking on the Stars
and Stripes.
   Susan Willhofft, 40, of Arlington, Va., was charged with
desecrating the flag, a felony, in the first such arrest resulting
from the exhibit at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago.
   The arrest came as two dozen critics of the exhibit picketed the
art school and a state senator picked the flag up, removing it from
the work, for the second day in a row.
   Willhofft's attorney acknowledged that she stepped on the flag,
but said she had no criminal or political motive.
   Attorney David E. Steinberg said the charge constituted
``harassment'' by the man who filed the complaint, Homer Choate, 47,
of suburban Lockport, who opposes the work.
   ``And I would think the state's attorney's office would have
something better to do than prosecute an innocent tourist,''
Steinberg added.
   At issue is a work by art student Scott Tyler titled ``What is
the Proper Way to Display a U.S. Flag?'' which is part of a minority
students' exhibit.
   The work features a montage of photographs depicting flag-draped
coffins and South Koreans burning the American flag, plus a book
that invites viewer comments.
   A U.S. flag is positioned on the floor in front of the book in
such a way that viewers are likely to step on the flag to write in
the book.
   The exhibit was closed to the public last weekend after veterans
groups complained it was illegal and disrespectful to the flag and
sued to try to force the school to remove it from the floor.
   Following a circuit judge's ruling Thursday, the show reopened.
   On Friday, state Sen. Walter Dudycz was detained briefly by
officers after he picked the flag up from the floor.
   He did it again on Saturday, and asked the Cook County State's
Attorney's office to decide whether the exhibit violates laws
against desecrating the flag. The flag was put back in the exhibit.
   Willhofft, who teaches grades 6-8, was attending a conference of
the National Association of Independent Schools, said another of her
attorneys, Lawrence S. Schaner.
   ``She had a free day, she was going to have lunch, she was going
to shop at Marshall Field,'' Schaner said. ``She had no intention of
making a political protest. She just went to see the famous Art
Institute of Chicago.
   ``She stepped on the flag,'' he said. ``She wanted to see what
was in the book.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
