<FIRST>u w AM-Tower 3rdLd-Writethru a0643 03-04 0871</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0643,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Maintaining Public Role in Nomination Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``We could ...'' to
UPDATE with Tower comments in newspaper interview. DELETES last graf to
tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary-designate John Tower has
moved out front in the Bush administration effort to salvage his
nomination, pleading the case publicly and setting the stage for a
possible last-ditch stand on the Senate floor.
   A White House official insisted Saturday the effort is not a lost
cause.
   ``We've still got some good prospects,'' among Democrats who
would be needed to provide a majority vote in Tower's favor, said
the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``We could still pull it out,'' the official said. ``I admit it's
very tough.''
   Tower, in comments published in Sunday editions of The Washington
Post, said the Senate would be ``damning the president's judgment''
if it rejects his nomination and said he will not withdraw unless
requested to do so by the president.
   ``The important thing is a majority of the Senate is going to
subordinate the president's judgment to its own in the selection of
people that the president feels he can rely on,'' Tower said in the
interview with a small group of reporters.
   Tower, who has pledged to abstain from alcoholic beverages if he
becomes defense secretary, reiterated his contention that he does
not have a drinking problem but said he has not stopped drinking
entirely.
   ``I still have a glass of wine in the evening with dinner,
although it's not on a daily basis,'' he said.
   As the number of Democrats on record against the nomination grew,
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole raised the prospect of bringing
Tower to the Senate floor to answer allegations against him.
   ``The request would be that John Tower be allowed to come to this
chamber, to stand in this well, and to answer his critics
face-to-face, charge-by-charge, rumor-by-rumor and fact-by-fact,''
the Kansas Republican said Friday.
   Dole did not formally ask permission for Tower, once a senator
himself, to speak from the floor, but said he was considering
introducing such a motion.
   ``If we owe Senator Tower anything, we owe him the right to say,
`I've had my day in court,''' Dole said.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said he would be ``happy
to consider any request'' by the minority leader, but gave no
indication on how the proposal would fare.
   If Tower came to the floor to answer questions, it would be the
first such instance for a Cabinet nominee and only the sixth time in
Senate history for a non-member to be questioned.
   On three occasions in the 1800s, newspaper reporters were called
before the Senate to answer questions about where they obtained
leaked information from closed Senate proceedings which appeared in
their stories.
   In 1933, the Senate sergeant at arms was called before the
chamber to answer questions about an article he had published
alleging that senators were selling their votes. And in 1934, three
airline officials were called to answer questions about government
contracting with airmail carriers.
   In the meantime, Tower planned to appear on a major network
interview show, CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation.'' The national
television appearance follows a week in which the embattled nominee
pledged to abstain from alcohol if confirmed and lashed out at the
double-standard that existed in the Senate _ all attempts to help
his faltering cause.
   The need for last-ditch efforts came in the wake of President
Bush's inability to convince a single Democrat to support the
nominee. The administration conducted two days of intensive lobbying
with the president holding one-on-one Oval Office sessions with
swing Democrats and Vice President Dan Quayle courting senators on
Capitol Hill.
   Quayle, on a weekend ski trip to New Hampshire, said Saturday
that once Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
came out against the nomination, ``we knew that it would be an
uphill battle.''
   ``This nomination hinges really on one individual in the Senate
and that is the chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee,''
Quayle said. ``Once he decided to go against the president we knew
that it was going to be difficult.''
   The numbers against the nomination continued to rise on Friday.
Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said the nation ``cannot take a
chance'' with Tower.
   DeConcini, who met privately at the White House with Bush earlier
this week and had hinted he might support the nominee, said Tower
``is not the proper person for this sensitive position in these
critical times.''
   An Associated Press survey of senators showed 47 Democrats and
Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., either solidly against the nomination
or leaning against, and 40 Republicans either solidly committed or
leaning toward confirmation. The Democrats hold a 55-45 majority in
the Senate.
   On Friday, Republican senators Phil Gramm of Texas and Trent Lott
of Mississippi huddled on the Senate floor over a major
administration concern _ Pressler.
   Among the other senators Republicans hope to convince is
conservative Democrat Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut.
   Jim Kennedy, an aide to Lieberman, said the senator planned to
``take the weekend to get away from the Washington distraction and
give it serious consideration in private.''
</TEXT>
