<FIRST>r a AM-AryanWoodstock 1stLd-Writethru a0615 03-04 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aryan Woodstock, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Protesters Jeer Whites-Only Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with scuffling, reflect revised
crowd estimate, edit for transition; picks up 5th graf, ``Asked about ...;''
SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Organizer Tom ...,'' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with revised
crowd estimate, description of rally site; picks up 10th graf pvs, ``The
event ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAPA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 protesters jeered at up to 100
neo-Nazi skinheads attending a white supremacist rally that had been
billed as an ``Aryan Woodstock,'' and some demonstrators scuffled
with a Ku Klux Klansman.
   About 200 police, some in riot gear, kept the demonstrators in a
soggy field about a mile from the whites-only gathering in Napa
County about 40 miles northeast of San Francisco.
   As a cold rain fell, protesters yelled ``Nazis go home!'' and
other taunts, and wielded placards with such messages as ``My Family
Died Because of Facism.''
   The protesters became enraged when a man who identified himself
as Bill Albers of the Modesto chapter of the Klan tried to walk
through the crowd. Albers and some of the demonstrators scuffled.
Gravel and sticks flew until law enforcement officers using
nightsticks brought the crowd under control.
   No arrests or injuries were reported earlier, but William
Herrell, 88, of San Jose, was slightly injured earlier when he was
dragged across a barbed-wire fence by demonstrators when he tried
unsuccessfully to enter the rally.
   Asked about the skinheads, Herrell said, ``I think they're
wonderful people.''
   ``I don't want to destroy other races. I just want to keep them
separate,'' Bob Spittler, a member of the Aryan National Socialists,
said as the rally began Friday night.
   Among the protesters Saturday was Irv Rubin of Los Angeles,
national chairman of the Jewish Defense League.
   ``People of good will cannot ignore this,'' Rubin said. ``No
matter how small their number, there has to be a statement against
their ideology. This is a battle of humanity versus the forces of
evil ... if we don't expose it, it's kind of like letting a cancer
grow on the body politic.''
   Organizer Tom Metzger, a former Klan leader who heads a group
called White Aryan Resistance, had estimated that 2,000 people would
attend, but law enforcement officials estimated attendance at 30 to
100.
   Associated Press photographer Pete Leabo, who flew over the rally
site in a helicopter, said he saw about 20 skinheads, many of them
under a tarp.
   Nazi flags decorated the rally, Leabo said.
   The event was initially billed as an ``Aryan Woodstock'' because
organizers had hoped to present performances by the skinhead bands
Midtown Boot Boys from Oklahoma, the Hammerheads from Wisconsin and
Hakenkreuz from Detroit.
   However, Napa County Superior Judge W. Scott Snowden ruled that a
permit was needed for the musical portion of the event. Snowden
rejected the county's argument that the assembly would be a public
nuisance.
   Metzger, who had argued a permit was not needed because the
concert was to be held on private property and admission was by
invitation only, decided to go ahead with the political portion of
the rally.
   Officials closed nearby state Highway 12 at Interstate 80 in
Fairfield and a road near Highway 29 to head off trouble.
   The scene was tense, as demonstrators leaned over barbed-wire
fences, screaming at a handful of skinheads watching them from atop
a nearby hill. At one point, about six skinheads who tried to get
into the rally got caught between police lines and protesters
yelling insults.
   The white power rally was held on land owned by Dr. Howard C.
Lonsdale of nearby Vallejo. Lonsdale fled Nazi Germany in 1937 with
his Jewish family when he was 4 years old, family friend Leo Coon
told The Sacramento Bee.
   Lonsdale, a prominent 55-year-old specialist, had been told the
gathering was to be an environmental rally but did not back out when
he learned its true nature because he feared reprisals, said Coon,
acting as Lonsdale's spokesman.
   ``Would you like your house pushed over the hill? That's why he
hasn't spoken out against them,'' said Coon.
   ``He was told by the group that if he canceled out of this lease,
they'd sue ... him, they'd ruin his practice,'' Coon added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
