<FIRST>r a AM-EspionageArrests     03-04 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Espionage Arrests,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aviation Supply Clerk, Apprentice Accused Of Spying, Stealing Parts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A naval supply clerk and a naval storekeeper
were arrested on charges of espionage and stealing $150,000 worth of
classified military parts and electronic components, the Navy said
Saturday.
   Donald Wayne King and Ronald Dean Graf, both 23 and assigned to
Naval Air Station New Orleans, were arrested Friday, said Senior
Chief Gerald Black, the base's spokesman.
   ``Classified military aircraft parts containing sensitive
technology and U.S. Navy electronics, (and) aircraft components
valued at more than $150,000 were recovered during the arrests,''
Black said in a statement.
   Graf, an airman aviation storekeeper, and King, an airman
apprentice aviation storekeeper, will be held in the Navy brig at
Pensacola, Fla., until their courts-martial, Black said.
   The two men were charged with espionage, theft of government
property, sale of sensitive and classified aircraft parts and
selling cocaine.
   Wayne Clookie, head of the Naval Investigative Service office in
New Orleans, said he didn't know what the motive was in the case.
   The investigation began Jan. 30, when someone who was offered
information and aircraft parts alerted the Naval Investigative
Service, Clookie said.
   He said an undercover agent posing as a buyer from a foreign
government got in touch with King and Graf. Clookie wouldn't say
which government.
   The two men _ whose jobs gave them access to parts, manuals and
other information _ sold about 30 items to the agent, said Clookie.
   King and Graf offered to steal and sell classified information,
aircraft parts, technical manuals, schematic drawings of weapons
systems and communication information, but didn't follow through on
everything, he said.
   ``Some money did change hands'' during the investigation, Clookie
said, but he refused to say how much on the grounds that the
information might jeopardize the prosecution.
   Clookie said there was no indication anyone else was involved.
</TEXT>
