<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-US     03-04 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Detains Nine School Buses With 100 American Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stopped nine buses carrying
about 100 American children for about three hours Friday because the
vehicles did not have proper license plates.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Southern Command, the U.S. military
headquarters for Latin America, said the action was ``arbitrary .. .
part of a campaign ... to restrict the movement of U.S. forces in
Panama.''
   All the buses had ``U.S. Navy'' painted on their sides, which
allows them to travel in the Panama City, said the spokesman, who
would not let his name be used.
   The buses were carrying children of U.S. Southern Command
employees in Panama.
   Police are part of the Panama Defense Forces led by Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noreiga, the country's de facto ruler, who has been indicted
in the United States for drug trafficking and laundering money.
Washington has imposed economic sanctions in an effort to remove him.
   Lt. Col. Aquilino Sieiro, a spokesman for the Panamanian
military, said in a telephone interview the buses did not have the
right license plates, but refused to explain. He also said, without
elaboration, that ``the incident is part of a disinformation
campaign and another provocation.''
   Along with the headquarters operation, the United States has
about 10,000 military personnel in Panama to defend the Panama Canal.

</TEXT>
