<FILEID>AP-NR-03-04-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     03-04 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Will Not Take Part in Elections, Government Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Friday that Burma's
ruling military junta will ``return to the barracks'' next year
after handing over power to an elected parliament.
   The military has held sway in this Southeast Asian nation for 27
years.
   At a weekly news conference, government spokesman Kyaw Sann
denied rumors that the military would participate in general
elections next year or that individual officers would resign
commissions to take part.
   ``They (the military) will hand over power to the new parliament
and return to the barracks,'' he said.
   Kyaw Sann also warned Burma's newly formed political parties to
avoid links with foreign diplomatic missions in Rangoon.
   He said some parties were closely linked with such missions, but
gave no details.
   Under a proposed election law announced on Wednesday, government
employees, including military personnel and police, cannot run for
election. The proposal is being reviewed by Burma's 233 political
parties and the general public.
   In September, Gen. Saw Maung and a group of military officers
crushed pro-democracy demonstrations here. The general, now head of
a military government, promised general elections in early 1990 and
the end of one-party rule.
   At another news conference, Finance and Trade Minister Col. Abel
announced Friday that as of April 1, government workers' salaries
will be raised anywhere from 20 percent to 109 percent and the
minimum wage will be nearly doubled.
   Salaries of armed forces personnel will be raised on a sliding
scale at rates similar to those of the civil servants. There are
about 1.2 million government employes, including members of the
armed forces.
   Abel said increased tax collections and greater production at
state enterprises would offset any inflationary effects.
   Civil servants have long complained about low wages and rising
prices. Many joined anti-government demonstrations last year.
   Salaries now range from $34 to $258 a month.
   The minimum daily wage of $1.33 will be raised to $2.34. Pensions
of retired government workers will also be increased.
   In another development, Thai border patrol police at Tak,
Thailand, said Karen guerrillas kept up attacks on the Burmese
village of Myawaddy on Friday, firing mortar rounds that killed
three villagers and wounded nine.
   Police Lt. Col. Manit Subsai-on said Burmese troops replied with
artillery and mortar fire.
   According to Thai military intelligence reports, the Karens have
been attacking the village, just inside the Burmese border, in
retaliation for an army offensive on a Karen stronghold 38 miles
away.
   The Karens for four decades have been fighting for greater
autonomy.
</TEXT>
