<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     03-04 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodriguez Promises To Find, Extradite Nazi War Criminals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish group met with Gen. Andres
Rodriguez on Friday and said the military ruler promised to find two
Nazi war criminals believed living in this country.
   Rabbi Martin M. Rosenthal, director of B'nai B'rith
Anti-Defamation League's department of Latin American Affairs, said
Rodriguez pledged to ``investigate, locate, detain and expel'' the
two war criminals.
   He said he would not identify the men for fear they would be
alerted to the search and flee to avoid capture.
   ``He reiterated that Paraguay will not be a ship for pirates or a
cave for thieves, and said they would rid the country of garbage
such as Nazi war criminals,'' Rosenthal said after a 25-minute
meeting with Rodriguez.
   Rodriguez, who seized power in the Feb. 3 coup that unseated
president Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, made no public comment following
the meeting.
   Rosenthal noted that Rodriguez' pledge of assistance contrasted
sharply with the cold reception given to such requests by the
Stroessner regime. In 1984, the newspaper of the ruling Colorado
Party mocked the efforts of Nazi hunter Beate Klarsfeld to locate
Josef Mengele.
   Under the 1976-83 military government in Argentina, requests for
information or arrest of alleged Nazi war criminals were ignored,
but since civilian President Raul Alfonsin took office, three have
been arrested, Rosenthal said.
   Also Friday, opposition leader Domingo Laino said his party may
participate in May 1 national elections even if some of its
electoral demands are denied. Laino, after meeting Rodriguez, told
reporters that ``the response to some of the terms of this package
can be positive and others negative and that does not mean we will
refuse to participate.
   ``We know we cannot reach the perfection of democracy overnight,
but we do want some reasonable conditions under which we can
participate,'' he said. ``We only want these elections to be an
improvement over the past.''
   During the nearly 35-year military Stroessner dictatorship,
several opposition parties refused to participate in elections,
claiming they were fraudulent.
   The National Accord alliance of three opposition parties has
asked Rodriguez to delay elections until at least Sept. 1 to give
them time to register supporters and organize campaigns. They also
hope to eliminate a statute that allots two-thirds of the seats in
congress to the party that wins a majority of votes.
   The Colorado Party, in power since 1947, is widely expected to
dominate the elections. Rodriguez is the party's presidential
candidate.
</TEXT>
