<FIRST>r i AM-Irish-FuneralKiller     03-04 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish-Funeral Killer,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protestant Convicted of Killing Mourners at IRA Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Protestant extremist was
convicted on Friday of killing six people, including three shot at
an IRA funeral, and was sentenced to life with the recommendation
that he serve at least 30 years.
   Michael Stone, 33, raised a clenched fist and shouted ``Long live
Ulster! No surrender!'' as he was led away at Belfast Crown Court.
   Judge Eoin Higgins said the people of Northern Ireland had a
right to long protection from such a ``dangerous and ruthless
criminal.''
   Police moved in to separate Roman Catholic and Protestant
spectators who jeered at each other as Stone was taken away.
   Stone called himself a ``free-lance'' killer for outlawed
sectarian organizations, but denied membership in groups that attack
the British province's Catholic minority.
   He told police he went to the funeral to kill Irish Republican
Army political leaders he knew would attend the burial in March 1988
of three IRA members killed by British commandos in Gibraltar.
   The IRA has waged a 20-year guerrilla war to drive the British
from Northern Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province
with the Irish Republic, which is overwhelmingly Catholic.
   Stone followed mourners from St. Agnes Catholic Church in Belfast
to the Milltown Cemetery and got past IRA security men by saying
their slogan in Gaelic: ``Our day will come.''
   As the funeral began, he lobbed grenades into the crowd and
opened fire with two guns.
   He said there were too many children and he could not shoot at
his intended targets from Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing:
Gerry Adams, the president; vice president Martin McGuinness, and
senior party official Danny Morrison.
   At one point, he told police, he gave a little girl a coin to
move away from him.
   The crowd pursued as Stone ran between tombstones shooting,
caught him and beat him until police took him away.
   Prosecutor Ronnie Appleton said when the trial opened Feb. 20
that, when police told him he had killed at least two people, Stone
replied: ``Brilliant. I am game for anything.''
   Stone also was convicted of killing Paddy Brady, a milkman, in
Belfast; Dermot Hackett, a bread deliver, near Omagh, and workman
Kevin McPolin at Lisburn.
</TEXT>
