<FIRST>r w AM-DunkleResignation     03-04 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dunkle Resignation,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>FWS Chief Quits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank H. Dunkle, director of the Fish and
Wildlife Service, has submitted his resignation to Interior
Secretary Manuel Lujan, a spokesman for the agency said Friday.
   The spokesman, Mike Smith, said he didn't know why Dunkle
resigned or what his future plans are. Interior sources, declining
to be identified, have said Dunkle made no secret that he would have
liked to remain at his current post in the new administration.
   Smith said Dunkle informed regional directors of the agency
Friday that he planned to leave his post as director of the Fish and
Wildlife Service March 15.
   On several occasions, Lujan has said he plans to replace key
bureau directors at the Interior Department as part of the normal
transition from one administration to another.
   But Dunkle also has been the center of some controversy.
   Allegations surfaced last month that Dunkle had interceded on the
behalf of Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Tex., after it was learned that Gramm's
property on Maryland's Eastern Shore was under surveillance by Fish
Wildlife Service officials.
   The officials suspected that birds were being baited for hunting
on the property, a practice that violates hunting laws.
   Dunkle denied that he had acted improperly. He said Gramm only
was told that bait had been spotted by routine aerial surveillance
on water near Gramm's property and that Fish and Wildlife officials
notified the senator to either not hunt or clean it up.
   Dunkle has maintained that such advisories are routine.
   Gramm has said that he does not use the property for hunting, but
that he does feed ducks occasionally. Dunkle at the time said Gramm
asked him to keep him advised if people broke the law on his
property.
</TEXT>
