<TEXT>
   Charles Lewis, one of the central figures in a
pair of federal investigation of Mayor Marion Barry, was arrested in
the Virgin Islands on Friday for allegedly selling cocaine to
undercover FBI agents, the FBI announced.
   Lewis allegedly sold six to seven grams of the drug to the agents
on St. Thomas and he has been charged with two counts of
distributing cocacine, according to W. Douglas Gow, an FBI spokesman.
   Lewis will be arraigned on the Caribbean island, the FBI
officials said.
   Lewis, 48, is a central figure in the investigations of Barry.
The two men are friends.
   After Lewis' arrest, Barry's office issued a statement saying
Barry was surprised.
   ``To my knowledge he (Charles Lewis) has never been arrested or
involved with any illegal activities,'' Barry said. ``I would be
shocked if these allegations about him turn out to be true.''
   Barry said he was also aware that Lewis' arrest would also
``raise the specter that something illegal happened'' when Barry
visited Lewis at a downtown hotel Dec. 22. ``I want to repeat again
that I never saw any drugs or drug paraphernalia during my visits
with Lewis.''
   Lewis was the target of a police investigation in December when a
maid at the Washington hotel alleged that he offered her drugs in
exchange for sex. Two district police officers were at the hotel
attempting to buy drugs from Lewis, but the drug buy was called off
when the officers realized that Barry was visiting Lewis.
   A federal grand jury is now looking at the circumstances
surrounding Barry's visit to the hotel.
   A second investigation involving both Lewis and Barry focuses on
the city's joint personnel project with the Virgin Islands.
   Lewis was in the charge of the project, but was fired last April
when officials in St. Thomas became concerned about cost overruns.
Barry and other top district officials ran up hotel and restaurant
bills of more than $37,000 in connection with the project.
