<FIRST>r a AM-DeadMan'sLetter     03-04 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dead Man's Letter,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letter From Dead Man Implicates Two In Girl's 1981 Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents may be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men in custody Friday in the
1981 kidnapping and killing of an 11-year-old girl, were linked to
the crime by a third man who confessed in a letter mailed after his
death, police said.
   Christine Anderson was last seen getting into a car on Aug. 31,
1981. Her disappearance set off a widespread search in the Fort
Lauderdale area, but no trace of her was found until her body was
found in a field six months later.
   Police had been unable to come up with any clues in the case
since then.
   On Dec. 16, a man named Frank Maxwell died in an automobile
accident in Texas, and his brother complied with his request to mail
a sealed letter to Fort Lauderdale police.
   The letter confessed to Maxwell's involvement in Christine's
disappearance and death, and linked two other men to the case,
police said.
   ``I would imagine throughout the years (Maxwell's) conscience was
bothering him,'' said Sgt. Tom Carney, of the Broward County
Sheriff's homicide unit.
   Gilbert Anthony Hall, 26, of Oakland Park, was arrested on Monday
and is being held in the Broward County Jail. Anthony Rodriguez, 29,
was arrested on Thursday in Kinnelon, N.J., police said. They were
charged with kidnapping and first-degree murder.
   ``There was no inkling at all that these people had anything to
do with'' Christine's death, said Fort Lauderdale police spokesman
Ott Cefkin.
   Maxwell's letter said Hall picked up Christine and took her to
his mobile home, where she was sedated and apparently raped numerous
times, according to a court document.
   Questioned by detectives, Hall admitted to picking up the girl,
taking her to the trailer where he lived with Maxwell and Rodriguez
to have sex with her, but said Rodriguez and Maxwell killed her,
sheriff's spokesman Al Gordon said.
   Hall said that he gave Christine several drinks and that Maxwell
gave her pills, the arrest warrant says. The letter said the girl
was suffocated and her body was dumped.
   The letter was given to police in January but they would not
release its contents on Thursday.
   Christine's mother, Karen Green, said she has continued to think
about her daughter, but tried to live a normal life.
   ``I wondered, always about the details and how many people'' were
involved, she said. ``I think knowing will help a little bit. It
will help to know that two others (the suspects) will be sweating it
out.''
</TEXT>
