<HEAD>Eds: ADDS weekly price trends</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... like this.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures had a mixed week on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in March settled Friday at $4.32} a bushel,
down from $4.34 a week earlier; March corn rose to $2.78\ a bushel
from $2.71{; March oats slipped to $2.05{ a bushel from $2.06\; and
March soybeans advanced to $7.67} a bushel from $7.61.
   Most livestock and meat futures retreated on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   April live cattle dropped to 77.80 cents a pound from 78.15
cents; March feeder cattle fell to 82.42 cents a pound from 83.62
cents; April live hogs rose to 44.15 cents a pound from 43.52 cents;
and March frozen pork bellies dipped to 37.25 cents a pound from
37.42 cents.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange.
   April gold fell to $389.30 a troy ounce from $392.60; March
silver slipped to $5.801 a troy ounce from $5.925.
   Energy futures gained on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for April delivery rose to
$18.56 a barrel from $18.07; April heating oil rallied to 50.80
cents a gallon from 49.82 cents; and April unleaded gasoline
advanced to 51.53 cents a gallon from 51.17 cents.
