<FIRST>r f BC-GibraltarS&amp;L     03-04 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gibraltar S&amp;L,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Thrift Enters Regulatory Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gibraltar Financial Corp., one of
the nation's 10 biggest savings and loan companies, revealed Friday
it had agreed with federal regulators to restrict its activities in
hopes of stemming continued losses.
   The company also said it would require a substantial investment
from outside or a merger to maintain federally required capital
levels.
   The company, parent of the 86-branch Gibraltar Savings &amp; Loan,
with assets of $15 billion, has been losing money since late 1987,
and recently disclosed it expected 1988 losses to reach $71 million
to $76 million.
   Additionally, profit in the first quarter of 1989 will be cut by
a $20 million writeoff from the closing of Gibraltar MoneyCenter,
which makes loans out of state, the company said in a news release.
That closure is part of the supervisory agreement with the Federal
Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., the company said.
   The supervisory agreement had been expected since January, when
the company revealed that federal regulators had declared Gibraltar
to be in ``unsafe and unsound'' condition. That finding was made
despite the fact Gibraltar met federal capital requirements, which
govern how much cash the company must have available to back its
loans.
   The agreement with regulators restricts Gibraltar to making home
loans in California, Florida and Washington state, the company said.
A previous agreement to restrict growth remains in effect.
   ``It is evident we will be unable to maintain required capital
levels without a merger with or major investment by a third party,''
James Thayer, Gibraltar chairman, president and chief executive
officer, said in a news release. ``Any such transaction will require
significant FSLIC assistance ... There is no assurance that we will
be successful in these efforts.''
   Gibraltar started on its slide with losses on real estate loans.
Recently, it has been hurt by rising interest rates, which force it
to pay more to attract deposits than it earns in interest on
fixed-rate loans it made in the past.
</TEXT>
